}\n| length11 = 2:21\n\n| title12 = Self Destruction\n| writer12 = {{hlist|Dixson|Walker|Gitelman|Ellis|Asthon McCreight|Mario Dragoi}}\n| extra12 = {{hlist|McCreight|Mario Luciano|Keyel|Gitelman|Dart}}\n| length12 = 2:40\n\n| title13 = Time\n| note13 = featuring [[Snoh Aalegra]]\n| writer13 = {{hlist|Dixson|McCleaney|Walker|Gitelman|Elias|[[Snoh Aalegra|Snoh Nowrozi]]}}\n| extra13 = {{hlist|McCleaney|Keyel|Gitelman|Elias}}\n| length13 = 2:25\n}}\n\n==Charts==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Chart (2019)\n! scope=\"col\"| Peak<br />position\n|-\n{{album chart|BillboardCanada|61|artist=Boogie|rowheader=true|accessdate=February 15, 2019}}\n|-\n{{album chart|Netherlands|133|artist=Boogie|album=Everythings For Sale|rowheader=true|accessdate=February 15, 2019}}\n|-\n{{album chart|UKR&B|16|date=20190201|artist=Boogie|rowheader=true|accessdate=May 27, 2019}}\n|-\n{{album chart|Billboard200|28|artist=Boogie|rowheader=true|accessdate=February 15, 2019}}\n|-\n{{album chart|BillboardRandBHipHop|18|artist=Boogie|rowheader=true|accessdate=February 15, 2019}}\n|-\n{{album chart|BillboardRap|18|artist=Boogie|rowheader=true|accessdate=February 15, 2019}}\n|-\n{{album chart|BillboardDigital|11|artist=Boogie|rowheader=true|accessdate=February 15, 2019}}\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[2019 in hip hop music]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:2019 debut albums]]\n[[Category:Shady Records albums]]\n[[Category:Boogie (rapper) albums]]\n[[Category:Interscope Records albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Symbolyc One]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2019 album by American rapper Boogie}}\n{{use mdy dates|date=February 2019}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Everythings for Sale\n| type       = [[Studio album]]\n| artist     = [[Boogie (rapper)|Boogie]]\n| cover      = \n| alt        =\n| released   = January 25, 2019\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Hip hop music|Hip hop]]\n| length     = {{Duration|m=38|s=58}}\n| label      = {{hlist||[[Shady Records|Shady]]|[[Interscope Records|Interscope]]|[[LoveRenaissance|LVRN]]}}\n| producer   = {{hlist|[[Eminem]] (exec.)|Ashton McCreight|[[C. Ballin]]|Chris Blakk|Chris McCleaney|Dart|[[J.Oliver|Fresh Ayr]]|Good Lineage Music|Gwen Bunn|Jeff Gitelman|Keyel|Mario Luciano|Mark Raggio|Moses Elias|Nabeyin|Ollie Chanin|Ryan Feinberg|[[Symbolyc One|S1]]|Sean Matsukawa|Sha\u00e9 Universe|Streetrunner|Teej}}\n| prev_title = Thirst 48, Pt. II\n| prev_year  = 2016\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = Everythings for Sale\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = Self Destruction\n | single1date = May 25, 2018\n | single2     = Silent Ride\n | single2date = January 9, 2019\n}}\n}}\n'''''Everythings for Sale''''' {{sic}} is the debut [[studio album]] by American rapper [[Boogie (rapper)|Boogie]]. It was released on January 25, 2019, by [[Shady Records]], [[Interscope Records]], and [[LoveRenaissance]].<ref>https://www.instagram.com/p/Bs8csIQh4Wi/</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/boogie-announces-new-album-everythings-for-sale/|title=Boogie Announces New Album Everythings for Sale|website=Pitchfork|accessdate=25 January 2019}}</ref> The album includes [[guest appearance]]s from [[6lack]], [[Christian Scott]], [[Eminem]], [[JID]], and [[Snoh Aalegra]], with production mainly coming from Keyel, Jeff Gitelman, and Dart, among others.<ref>{{cite web |title=Boogie recruits Eminem, J.I.D., and more on Everythings For Sale |url=https://www.thefader.com/2019/01/23/boogie-eminem-everythings-for-sale |website=The Fader |accessdate=25 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Singles and promotion==\nThe album's first single, \"Self Destruction\", was released on May 25, 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.xxlmag.com/video/2018/05/boogie-self-destruction-video/|title=Boogie Shows Off His Super Powers in \"Self Destruction\" Video - XXL|first=Nick|last=Mojica|website=XXL Mag|accessdate=25 January 2019}}</ref> The promotional single \"Deja Vu\" was released for digital download on August 29, 2018, one day before his 29th birthday. The song was produced by Keyel and Sean Matsukawa.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/boogie-takes-to-lush-acoustic-guitars-on-deja-vu-new-song.1980111.html|title=Boogie Takes To Lush Acoustic Guitars On \"Deja Vu\"|website=HotNewHipHop|accessdate=25 January 2019}}</ref> The album's second single, \"Silent Ride\", was released on January 9, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thefader.com/2019/01/09/boogie-everythings-for-sale-silent-ride|title=Boogie to release new album Everything's for Sale|website=The FADER|accessdate=25 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn January 23, Boogie released a short-film for the album, produced by [[Riley Keough]], Gina Gammell, and Malcolm Washington. The idea came when Boogie was discussing what each song would look visually.<ref>{{cite web |title=Boogie Previews Debut Album With 'Everything's for Sale' Short Film |url=https://www.complex.com/music/2019/01/boogie-everythings-for-sale-short-film |website=Complex |accessdate=25 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\n{{Album ratings\n| MC = 82/100<ref name=\"Metacritic\">{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/music/everythings-for-sale/boogie/critic-reviews|title=Critic Reviews for Everything's For Sale|publisher=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=February 15, 2019}}</ref>\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/everythings-for-sale-mw0003247146|title=Everything's for Sale - Boogie {{!}} Songs, Reviews, Credits|last=Thomas|first=Fred|website=[[AllMusic]]|access-date=February 15, 2019}}</ref>\n| rev2 = ''[[Exclaim!]]''\n| rev2score = 8/10<ref>{{cite web|url=http://exclaim.ca/music/article/boogie-everythings_for_sale|title=Boogie Everything's For Sale|last=Mullin|first=Kyle|date=January 28, 2019|website=[[Exclaim!]]|access-date=February 15, 2019}}</ref>\n| rev3 = ''[[HipHopDX]]''\n| rev3score = 4.2/5<ref>{{cite web|url=https://hiphopdx.com/reviews/id.3353/title.review-boogies-honesty-makes-shady-debut-everythings-for-sale-remarkable|title=Review: Boogie's Honesty Makes Shady Debut \"Everything's For Sale\" Remarkable|last=McKrell|first=Aaron|date=January 31, 2019|website=[[HipHopDX]]|access-date=February 15, 2019}}</ref>\n| rev4 = ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]''\n| rev4score = 7.1/10<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/boogie-everythings-for-sale/|title=Boogie: Everything's for Sale|last=Alston|first=Trey|date=January 31, 2019|website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|access-date=February 15, 2019}}</ref> \n| rev5 = ''[[The 405 (website)|The 405]]''\n| rev5score = 8.5/10<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thefourohfive.com/music/review/review-boogie-delves-subtly-into-an-existential-crisis-via-the-irresistible-groove-of-everything-s-for-sale-154|title=Album Review: Boogie \u2013 Everything's for Sale|last=McMullen|first=Chase|date=January 28, 2019|website=[[The 405 (website)|The 405]]|access-date=February 15, 2019}}</ref>\n| rev6 = ''[[XXL (magazine)|XXL]]''\n| rev6score = 4/5<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.xxlmag.com/news/2019/02/boogie-everythings-for-sale-album-review/|title=Boogie Puts His Pain on Wax on 'Everything's For Sale' Album - XXL|last=Fox|first=Luke|date=February 1, 2019|website=[[XXL (magazine)|XXL]]|access-date=February 15, 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n\nUpon its release, the album has received widespread critical acclaim. Aaron McKrell of ''[[HipHopDX]]'' gave the album 4.2 out of 5, claiming it was \"worth fans' patience\" and an effective introduction to \"a troubled young man with a brilliant mind whose musings are starkly engaging\". Trey Alston from ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]'' said \"The Compton rapper's debut is smart, technically dazzling, and thoroughly sullen\". In a one-listen review, Yoh Phillips from ''DJBooth'' said \"Boogie reminds me of a film director who is able to turn every actor before their lens into a character that the audience feel as if they know personally\".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Phillips |first1=Yoh |title=Boogie 'Everythings for Sale' 1 Listen Album Review |url=https://djbooth.net/features/2019-01-25-boogie-everythings-for-sale-album-review |website=DJBooth |accessdate=25 January 2019}}</ref> The album was positively received by Complex Media's morning debate show \"Everyday Struggle\". The album's maturity and features were particularly well-liked.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/pop-culture/2019/01/young-dolph-lied-about-being-indie-boogies-debut-album-cole-bennetts-impact-everyday-struggle|title=Young Dolph Lied About Being Indie? Boogie's Debut Album, Cole Bennett's Impact - Everyday Struggle|website=Complex}}</ref> XXL Magazine lauded Boogie's no holds barred brand of self awareness, noting \"He doesn\u2019t have it all figured out. He gets sad and angry and knows he needs to improve\". The publication gave the album an \"XL\" on a \"S\" to \"XXL\" scale.\n\n==Commercial performance==\nThe album debuted at number 28 on the US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] and number 18 on the US [[Top R&B/Hip-Hop Albums]] chart, selling 18,397 [[album-equivalent units]] in its first week.<ref>{{cite web|author=0/1000CLOSE |url=https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/boogies-shady-debut-everythings-for-sale-first-week-numbers-news.71064.html |title=Boogie's Shady Debut \"Everything's For Sale\": First Week Numbers |publisher=Hotnewhiphop.com |date=2019-02-04 |accessdate=2020-02-28}}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\nCredits adapted from [[Tidal (service)|Tidal]],<ref>https://listen.tidal.com/album/102675993/credits</ref> [[Broadcast Music, Inc.|BMI]],<ref>https://repertoire.bmi.com/DetailView.aspx?detail=titleid&keyid=29742664&ShowNbr=0&ShowSeqNbr=0&blnWriter=True&blnPublisher=True&blnArtist=True&blnAltTitles=True</ref><ref>https://repertoire.bmi.com/DetailView.aspx?detail=titleid&keyid=29742561&ShowNbr=0&ShowSeqNbr=0&blnWriter=True&blnPublisher=True&blnArtist=True&blnAltTitles=True</ref><ref>https://repertoire.bmi.com/DetailView.aspx?detail=titleid&keyid=28551159&ShowNbr=0&ShowSeqNbr=0&blnWriter=True&blnPublisher=True&blnArtist=True&blnAltTitles=True</ref><ref>https://repertoire.bmi.com/DetailView.aspx?detail=titleid&keyid=29829393&ShowNbr=0&ShowSeqNbr=0&blnWriter=True&blnPublisher=True&blnArtist=True&blnAltTitles=True</ref> [[American Society of Composers, Authors and Publishers|ASCAP]],<ref>{{cite web|author=ACE |url=https://www.ascap.com/repertory#ace/work/896569601 |title=ACE Repertory |publisher=Ascap.com |date= |accessdate=2020-02-28}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=ACE |url=https://www.ascap.com/repertory#ace/work/896668953 |title=ACE Repertory |publisher=Ascap.com |date= |accessdate=2020-02-28}}</ref> [[AllMusic]],<ref>{{cite web|author=AllMusic Review by Fred Thomas |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/everythings-for-sale-mw0003247146 |title=Everything's for Sale - Boogie &#124; Songs, Reviews, Credits |publisher=AllMusic |date=2019-01-25 |accessdate=2020-02-28}}</ref> and [[Universal Music Publishing Group|UMPG]].<ref>https://www.umusicpub.com/us/Digital-Music-Library/album/87393/everythings-for-sale</ref>\n{{Track listing\n| extra_column = Producer(s)\n| total_length = 38:59\n\n| title1 = Tired/Reflections\n| writer1 = {{hlist|[[Boogie (rapper)|Anthony Dixson]]|Keyel Walker|Jeffrey Gitelman|Oliver Chanin|Moussa Elias|Gwendolyn Bunn|Sharon Ogo-Uzodike}}\n| extra1 = {{hlist|Keyel|Jeff Gitelman|Ollie Chanin|Moses Elias|Gwen Bunn|Sha\u00e9 Universe}}\n| length1 = 4:01\n\n| title2 = Silent Ride\n| writer2 = {{hlist|Dixson|Walker|Gitelman}}\n| extra2 = {{hlist|Keyel|Gitelman}}\n| length2 = 2:50\n\n| title3 = Swap Meet\n| writer3 = {{hlist|Dixson|Walker|Gitelman|Ryan Feinberg|Mark Raggio}}\n| extra3 = {{hlist|Keyel|Gitelman|Feinberg|Raggio}}\n| length3 = 2:26\n\n\n| title4 = Lolsmh\n| note4 = Interlude\n| writer4 = {{hlist|Dixson|Walker|Gitelman|Christopher McClenney}}\n| extra4 = {{hlist|Keyel|Gitelman|Chris McClenney}}\n| length4 = 4:15\n\n| title5 = Soho\n| note5 = featuring [[JID]]\n| writer5 = {{hlist|Dixson|Walker|Gitelman|[[JID|Destin Route]]|Afolabi Osinulu}}\n| extra5 = {{hlist|Teej|Keyel|Gitelman}}\n| length5 = 2:13\n\n| title6 = Skydive\n| writer6 = {{hlist|Dixson|Walker|Gitelman|Darttny Ellis|Sean Matsukawa}}\n| extra6 = {{hlist|Dart|Keyel|Gitelman|Matsukawa}}\n| length6 = 3:29\n\n| title7 = Live 95\n| writer7 = {{hlist|Dixson|Walker|Gitelman|Edgar Panford|[[C. Ballin|Chris Jackson]]|[[Gryphon (band)|Brian Gulland]]}}\n| extra7 = {{hlist|Nabeyin|Keyel|Gitelman|[[C. Ballin]]}}\n| length7 = 2:15\n\n| title8 = Rainy Days\n| note8 = featuring [[Eminem]]\n| writer8 = {{hlist|Dixson|Walker|Gitelman|[[Eminem|Marshall Mathers]]|Nicholas Warwar|Tarik Azzouz|[[Symbolyc One|Larry Griffin, Jr.]]|[[J.Oliver|Jeffery Robinson]]|Maxime Breton}}\n| extra8 = {{hlist|Streetrunner|Azzouz|[[Symbolyc One|S1]]|[[J.Oliver|Fresh Ayr]]|Good Lineage Music|Keyel|Gitelman}}\n| length8 = 3:54\n\n| title9 = Skydive II\n| note9 = featuring [[6lack]]\n| writer9 = {{hlist|Dixson|Ellis|Walker|Gitelman|[[6lack|Ricardo Valentine]]}}\n| extra9 = {{hlist|Dart|Keyel|Gitelman}}\n| length9 = 2:53\n\n| title10 = Whose Fault\n| note10 = featuring [[Christian Scott]]\n| writer10 = {{hlist|Dixson|Ellis|Walker|Gitelman|[[Christian Scott]]|Chris Daniels|Kolseta Moore}}\n| extra10 = {{hlist|Dart|Keyel|Gitelman|Scott|Chris Blakk}}\n| length10 = 3:10\n\n| title11 = No Warning\n| note11  = featuring Sha\u00e9 Universe\n| writer11 = {{hlist|Dixson|Ellis|Walker|Gitelman}}\n| extra11 = {{hlist|Dart|Keyel|Gitelman}}\n| length11 = 2:21\n\n| title12 = Self Destruction\n| writer12 = {{hlist|Dixson|Walker|Gitelman|Ellis|Asthon McCreight|Mario Dragoi}}\n| extra12 = {{hlist|McCreight|Mario Luciano|Keyel|Gitelman|Dart}}\n| length12 = 2:40\n\n| title13 = Time\n| note13 = featuring [[Snoh Aalegra]]\n| writer13 = {{hlist|Dixson|McCleaney|Walker|Gitelman|Elias|[[Snoh Aalegra|Snoh Nowrozi]]}}\n| extra13 = {{hlist|McCleaney|Keyel|Gitelman|Elias}}\n| length13 = 2:25\n}}\n\n==Charts==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Chart (2019)\n! scope=\"col\"| Peak<br />position\n|-\n{{album chart|BillboardCanada|61|artist=Boogie|rowheader=true|accessdate=February 15, 2019}}\n|-\n{{album chart|Netherlands|133|artist=Boogie|album=Everythings For Sale|rowheader=true|accessdate=February 15, 2019}}\n|-\n{{album chart|UKR&B|16|date=20190201|artist=Boogie|rowheader=true|accessdate=May 27, 2019}}\n|-\n{{album chart|Billboard200|28|artist=Boogie|rowheader=true|accessdate=February 15, 2019}}\n|-\n{{album chart|BillboardRandBHipHop|18|artist=Boogie|rowheader=true|accessdate=February 15, 2019}}\n|-\n{{album chart|BillboardRap|18|artist=Boogie|rowheader=true|accessdate=February 15, 2019}}\n|-\n{{album chart|BillboardDigital|11|artist=Boogie|rowheader=true|accessdate=February 15, 2019}}\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[2019 in hip hop music]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:2019 debut albums]]\n[[Category:Shady Records albums]]\n[[Category:Boogie (rapper) albums]]\n[[Category:Interscope Records albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Symbolyc One]]\n", "name_user": "Hybrid27", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Everythings_for_Sale"}
{"title_page": "Sirasa TV", "text_new": "{{Infobox television channel\n| name              = Sirasa TV<br/>\u0dc3\u0dd2\u0dbb\u0dc3 TV\n| logofile          = Sirasa TV logo.png\n| logosize          = \n| logocaption       = \n| logoalt           = Sirasa TV logo\n| logo2             =\n| established       = \n| airdate           = \n| launch            = 1998\n| closed date       = \n| picture format    =[[576i]] [[SDTV]] \n| share             = \n| share as of       = \n| share source      = \n| network           = [[MTV Channel]]\n| owner             = [[Capital Maharaja]]\n| parent            = \n| key people        = \n| slogan            = ''The People's Channel''\n| motto             =\n| country           = [[Sri Lanka]]\n| language          = [[Sinhalese language|Sinhalese]]\n| broadcast area    = Sri Lanka\n| affiliates        =\n| headquarters      = [[Colombo]]\n| former names      = \n| replaced names    = \n| replaced by names = \n| sister names      = [[TV 1 (Sri Lanka)|TV 1]]<br>[[Shakthi TV]]\n| timeshift names   = \n| web               = {{URL|www.sirasatv.lk}}\n|  terr serv 1       = [[UHF]] ([[Union Place]])<br/>([[Free-to-air|FTA]])\n| terr chan 1       = Channel 23\n| terr serv 2       = [[UHF]] ([[Namunukula]])<br/>([[Free-to-air|FTA]])\n| terr chan 2       = Channel 29\n| terr serv 3       = [[UHF]] ([[Hunnasgiriya]])<br/>([[Free-to-air|FTA]])\n| terr chan 3       = Channel 58\n| terr serv 4       = [[UHF]] ([[Gammaduwa]])<br/>([[Free-to-air|FTA]])\n| terr chan 4       = Channel 23\n| terr serv 5       = [[UHF]] ([[Hanthana]])<br/>([[Free-to-air|FTA]])\n| terr chan 5       = Channel 29\n| terr serv 6       = [[UHF]] ([[Gongala]])<br/>([[Free-to-air|FTA]])\n| terr chan 6       = Channel 29\n| terr serv 7       = [[UHF]] ([[Minuwangala]])<br/>([[Free-to-air|FTA]])\n| terr chan 7       = Channel 58\n| terr serv 8       = [[UHF]] ([[Nuwara Eliya]])<br/>([[Free-to-air|FTA]])\n| terr chan 8       = Channel 27\n| terr serv 9       = [[UHF]] ([[Matugama]])<br/>([[Free-to-air|FTA]])\n| terr chan 9       = Channel 51\n| terr serv 10      = TV Lanka Digital TV ([[Pay Television|Pay TV]])\n| terr chan 10      = Channel 5\n| sat serv 1        = [[Dialog TV]]\n| sat chan 1        = 8\n\n| sat serv 2        = [[Dish TV Sri Lanka]]\n| sat chan 2        =2513\n| cable serv 1      = [[Ask Cable Vision]]\n| cable chan 1      = 5\n| iptv serv 1       = [[PEO TV]]\n| iptv chan 1       = 10\n| online serv 1     =\n| online chan 1     = {{url|http://www.sirasatv.lk/live|Watch live}}\n}}\n'''Sirasa TV''' is a [[Digital television|digital]], [[Terrestrial television|terrestrial]] [[television network]] in [[Sri Lanka]]. It is the sister channel of '[[TV One (Sri Lanka)|TV One]]' (Previously [[MTV]] and MTV Sports) which was established in 1992. [[Sirasa TV]] was Started in 1998 to similar itself to their Radio network Sirasa FM. Sirasa TV is owned by the [[Sri Lanka]]n [[business conglomerate]] [https://www.capitalmaharaja.com The Capital Maharaja Organization Ltd] together with Gregson Holdings Ltd. Since then, another multi-national company - International Media Management - has also invested in MTV. It broadcasts its programs mainly in [[Sinhala language|Sinhala]].\n\n==Attacks==\n\n===2009 New Year Attack and assassination===\nFifteen masked gunmen stormed the studio and transmission complex, and destroyed the main control room of the group on 6 January 2009.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.lankaenews.com/English/news.php?id=6933 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-05-29 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110713184104/http://www.lankaenews.com/English/news.php?id=6933 |archivedate=2011-07-13 }}</ref><ref>http://news.nidahasa.com/news.php?go=fullnews&newsid=657</ref> Investigations revealed that a [[Claymore mine]] was used for the attack.<ref>http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/7813043.stm</ref> Critics and observers linked the attack to the controversial reporting that was adopted in relation to the capture of [[Kilinochchi]] by Government Forces.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dailymirror.lk/DM_BLOG/Sections/frmNewsDetailView.aspx?ARTID=37161 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-05-29 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090309021837/http://www.dailymirror.lk/DM_BLOG/Sections/frmNewsDetailView.aspx?ARTID=37161 |archivedate=2009-03-09 }}</ref> Opposition political parties and associated media organizations accused the government of being responsible for the attack.\n\n==Teledramas==\n* [[Ye Hai Mohabbatein|Me Aadarayai]]\n* [[Diya Aur Baati Hum|Swapna]]\n* [[Naagin (2015 TV series)|Prema Dadayama 3]]\n* [[Kasautii Zindagii Kay (2018 TV series)|Praveena 2]]\n* [[Neela Pabalu]]\n* [[Mini Gang Dela]]\n* [[Oba Nisa]]\n* [[Descendants of the Sun|Himanthara]]\n\n==Other Popular Programs==\n*[[Sirasa Pentathlon]]\n*[[Sirasa Junior Super Star]]\n*[[Sirasa Film Star]]\n*[[Api Nodanna Live]]\n*[[Sri Lanka's Got Talent]]\n*[[Obada Lakshapathi Mamada Lakshapathi]] <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sundaytimes.lk/100926/Magazine/sundaytimestvtimes_9.html |title=Sirasa to make Millionaires |publisher=Sunday Times |accessdate=29 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Past Hit Programs==\n*[[Sirasa Kumariya]] \n*[[Sirasa Dancing Star]]\n*[[Sirasa Superstar]] \n*[[Sirasa Platinum Awards]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.sirasatv.lk/ Official website]\n* [https://tvlankalive.com/sirasa-tv-live-youtube/ Sirasa TV LIVE]\n\n{{Media of Sri Lanka}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sirasa Tv}}\n[[Category:MTV Channel]]\n[[Category:Sinhala-language television stations]]\n[[Category:Television channels and stations established in 1998]]\n[[Category:1998 establishments in Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:Media in Colombo]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox television channel\n| name              = Sirasa TV<br/>\u0dc3\u0dd2\u0dbb\u0dc3 TV\n| logofile          = Sirasa TV logo.png\n| logosize          = \n| logocaption       = \n| logoalt           = Sirasa TV logo\n| logo2             =\n| established       = \n| airdate           = \n| launch            = 1998\n| closed date       = \n| picture format    =[[576i]] [[SDTV]] \n| share             = \n| share as of       = \n| share source      = \n| network           = [[MTV Channel]]\n| owner             = [[Capital Maharaja]]\n| parent            = \n| key people        = \n| slogan            = ''The People's Channel''\n| motto             =\n| country           = [[Sri Lanka]]\n| language          = [[Sinhalese language|Sinhalese]]\n| broadcast area    = Sri Lanka\n| affiliates        =\n| headquarters      = [[Colombo]]\n| former names      = \n| replaced names    = \n| replaced by names = \n| sister names      = [[TV 1 (Sri Lanka)|TV 1]]<br>[[Shakthi TV]]\n| timeshift names   = \n| web               = {{URL|www.sirasatv.lk}}\n|  terr serv 1       = [[UHF]] ([[Union Place]])<br/>([[Free-to-air|FTA]])\n| terr chan 1       = Channel 23\n| terr serv 2       = [[UHF]] ([[Namunukula]])<br/>([[Free-to-air|FTA]])\n| terr chan 2       = Channel 29\n| terr serv 3       = [[UHF]] ([[Hunnasgiriya]])<br/>([[Free-to-air|FTA]])\n| terr chan 3       = Channel 58\n| terr serv 4       = [[UHF]] ([[Gammaduwa]])<br/>([[Free-to-air|FTA]])\n| terr chan 4       = Channel 23\n| terr serv 5       = [[UHF]] ([[Hanthana]])<br/>([[Free-to-air|FTA]])\n| terr chan 5       = Channel 29\n| terr serv 6       = [[UHF]] ([[Gongala]])<br/>([[Free-to-air|FTA]])\n| terr chan 6       = Channel 29\n| terr serv 7       = [[UHF]] ([[Minuwangala]])<br/>([[Free-to-air|FTA]])\n| terr chan 7       = Channel 58\n| terr serv 8       = [[UHF]] ([[Nuwara Eliya]])<br/>([[Free-to-air|FTA]])\n| terr chan 8       = Channel 27\n| terr serv 9       = [[UHF]] ([[Matugama]])<br/>([[Free-to-air|FTA]])\n| terr chan 9       = Channel 51\n| terr serv 10      = TV Lanka Digital TV ([[Pay Television|Pay TV]])\n| terr chan 10      = Channel 5\n| sat serv 1        = [[Dialog TV]]\n| sat chan 1        = 8\n\n| sat serv 2        = [[Dish TV Sri Lanka]]\n| sat chan 2        =2513\n| cable serv 1      = [[Ask Cable Vision]]\n| cable chan 1      = 5\n| iptv serv 1       = [[PEO TV]]\n| iptv chan 1       = 10\n| online serv 1     =\n| online chan 1     = {{url|http://www.sirasatv.lk/live|Watch live}}\n}}\n'''Sirasa TV''' is a [[Digital television|digital]], [[Terrestrial television|terrestrial]] [[television network]] in [[Sri Lanka]]. It is the sister channel of '[[TV One]]' (Previously [[MTV]] and MTV Sports) which was established in 1992. [[Sirasa TV]] was Started in 1998 to similar itself to their Radio network Sirasa FM. Sirasa TV is owned by the [[Sri Lanka]]n [[business conglomerate]] [https://www.capitalmaharaja.com The Capital Maharaja Organization Ltd] together with Gregson Holdings Ltd. Since then, another multi-national company - International Media Management - has also invested in MTV. It broadcasts its programs mainly in [[Sinhala language|Sinhala]].\n\n==Attacks==\n\n===2009 New Year Attack and assassination===\nFifteen masked gunmen stormed the studio and transmission complex, and destroyed the main control room of the group on 6 January 2009.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.lankaenews.com/English/news.php?id=6933 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-05-29 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110713184104/http://www.lankaenews.com/English/news.php?id=6933 |archivedate=2011-07-13 }}</ref><ref>http://news.nidahasa.com/news.php?go=fullnews&newsid=657</ref> Investigations revealed that a [[Claymore mine]] was used for the attack.<ref>http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/7813043.stm</ref> Critics and observers linked the attack to the controversial reporting that was adopted in relation to the capture of [[Kilinochchi]] by Government Forces.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dailymirror.lk/DM_BLOG/Sections/frmNewsDetailView.aspx?ARTID=37161 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-05-29 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090309021837/http://www.dailymirror.lk/DM_BLOG/Sections/frmNewsDetailView.aspx?ARTID=37161 |archivedate=2009-03-09 }}</ref> Opposition political parties and associated media organizations accused the government of being responsible for the attack.\n\n==Teledramas==\n* [[Ye Hai Mohabbatein|Me Aadarayai]]\n* [[Diya Aur Baati Hum|Swapna]]\n* [[Naagin (2015 TV series)|Prema Dadayama 3]]\n* [[Kasautii Zindagii Kay (2018 TV series)|Praveena 2]]\n* [[Neela Pabalu]]\n* [[Mini Gang Dela]]\n* [[Oba Nisa]]\n* [[Descendants of the Sun|Himanthara]]\n\n==Other Popular Programs==\n*[[Sirasa Pentathlon]]\n*[[Sirasa Junior Super Star]]\n*[[Sirasa Film Star]]\n*[[Api Nodanna Live]]\n*[[Sri Lanka's Got Talent]]\n*[[Obada Lakshapathi Mamada Lakshapathi]] <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sundaytimes.lk/100926/Magazine/sundaytimestvtimes_9.html |title=Sirasa to make Millionaires |publisher=Sunday Times |accessdate=29 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Past Hit Programs==\n*[[Sirasa Kumariya]] \n*[[Sirasa Dancing Star]]\n*[[Sirasa Superstar]] \n*[[Sirasa Platinum Awards]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.sirasatv.lk/ Official website]\n* [https://tvlankalive.com/sirasa-tv-live-youtube/ Sirasa TV LIVE]\n\n{{Media of Sri Lanka}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sirasa Tv}}\n[[Category:MTV Channel]]\n[[Category:Sinhala-language television stations]]\n[[Category:Television channels and stations established in 1998]]\n[[Category:1998 establishments in Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:Media in Colombo]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toTV1(link changed toTV One (Sri Lanka)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sirasa_TV"}
{"title_page": "Reginald Hudlin", "text_new": "{{short description|American filmmaker}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Reginald Hudlin\n| image        = 10.5.17ReginaldHudlinByLuigiNovi1.jpg\n| alt          = Reginald Hudlin\n| caption      = Hudlin at the 2017 [[New York Comic Con]]\n| birth_name   = Reginald Alan Hudlin\n| birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1961|12|15}}\n| birth_place  = [[Centreville, Illinois]], U.S.\n| nationality  = [[United States|American]]\n| other_names  = Reggie Hudlin\n| occupation   = Film director<br/>Writer<br/>Producer\n| years_active = 1983&ndash;present\n| known_for    = ''[[House Party (film)|House Party]]''<br/> ''[[Django Unchained]]'' \n| home_town    = [[East St. Louis, Illinois]], U.S.\n| spouse       = {{marriage|Chrisette Suter|November 30, 2002}}\n| children     = 2\n| relatives    = [[Warrington Hudlin]] (brother)\n}}\n'''Reginald Alan Hudlin''' (born December 15, 1961) is an American film screenwriter, director and producer.<ref name=BlackDirectorsInHollywood-2003>{{cite book|last1=Donalson|first1=Melvin Burke|title=Black Directors in Hollywood|date=2003|publisher=University of Texas Press|location=Austin|isbn=978-0-292-79875-5|chapter=Chapter 9: Not Without Laughter: Directors of Comedy and Romance, Chapter 10: Off the Hook: Comedy and Romance with a Hip-Hop Flavor|oclc=55731956}}</ref> Along with his older brother [[Warrington Hudlin]], he is known as one of the '''Hudlin Brothers.'''<ref name=FilmComment-HouseParty-1990>{{cite journal|last1=Hudlin|first1=Reginald|last2=Hudlin|first2=Warrington|last3=Glicksman|first3=Marlaine|title=They Gotta Have It|journal=[[Film Comment]]|date=May 1990|volume=26|issue=3|pages=65\u201369|jstor=43454842}} {{Closed access}}</ref> From 2005 to 2008, Hudlin was President of Entertainment for [[Black Entertainment Television|Black Entertainment Television (BET)]]. Hudlin has also written numerous graphic novels.<ref name=SilverBullet-Interview-2005>{{cite news|last1=Encarnacion|first1=Jonathan|title=Uncompromising Articulation: Reginald Hudlin|url=http://silverbulletcomics.com/news/story.php?a=321|work=[[Silver Bullet Comic Books]]|date=13 April 2005|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20051125211734/http://silverbulletcomics.com/news/story.php?a=321|archivedate=25 November 2005}}</ref> He co-produced the [[88th Academy Awards]] ceremony in 2016 as well as other TV specials. Hudlin's breakout film was 1990's ''[[House Party (film)|House Party]]'',<ref name=Cineaste-HouseParty-1990>{{cite journal|last1=Hudlin|first1=Reginald|last2=Hudlin|first2=Warrington|last3=Kantor|first3=Michael|title=Tearing the Roof Off the Sucker: An Interview with Reginald and Warrington Hudlin|journal=[[Cineaste (magazine)|Cin\u00e9aste]]|date=1990|volume=18|issue=1|pages=22\u201323|jstor=41687018}} {{Closed access}}</ref> and he worked as a producer on [[Quentin Tarantino]]'s 2012 film, ''[[Django Unchained]]'', which earned him an [[Academy Awards|Academy Award]] nomination for [[Academy Award for Best Picture|Best Picture]]. He also directed the 1992 film ''[[Boomerang (1992 film)|Boomerang]]''.\n\n== Early life ==\nHudlin was born in [[Centreville, Illinois]], the son of Helen Hudlin (n\u00e9e Cason), a teacher who worked in special education, and Warrington W. Hudlin, Sr., an insurance executive and educator.<ref name=BlackDirectorsInHollywood-2003 />{{rp|234}} Hudlin's older brother, [[Warrington Hudlin]], is also a film director, as well as an actor and producer. Hudlin is the youngest, with middle brother, Christopher Hudlin, working with their father in the insurance business.{{citation needed|date=September 2017}}\n\nThe Hudlins grew up in [[East St. Louis, Illinois|East St. Louis]], [[Illinois]], where the family had deep roots.<ref name=NYTimes-HouseParty-1990>{{cite news|last1=Greenberg|first1=James|title=In Hollywood, Black Is In|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1990/03/04/movies/in-hollywood-black-is-in.html|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=4 March 1990}}</ref> The Hudlin Brothers are paternal great-great-grandsons of Peter and Nancy Hudlin, who were part of the [[Underground Railroad]]. Their great uncle was an influential tennis instructor named Richard A. Hudlin, who mentored [[Arthur Ashe]] and [[Althea Gibson]].<ref name=StLouisPostDispatch-UndergroundRR-2000>{{cite news|last1=Franklin|first1=Donald E.|title=Its History Rides on the Underground Railroad|work=[[St. Louis Post-Dispatch]]|date=27 February 2000|location=St. Louis|page=C.1|issn=1930-9600|id={{ProQuest|40400223}}}} {{Closed access}}</ref>\n\nThe Hudlins attended [[Katherine Dunham]]'s [[Performing Arts Training Center|Center for the Performing Arts]], an experimental school, Warrington for high school and Reginald for after school martial arts classes.<ref name=NPR-Dunham-Obit-2006>{{cite news|last1=Elliott|first1=Debbie|last2=Dryden|first2=Jim|last3=Dunham|first3=Katherine|title=Katherine Dunham Helped Teach the World to Dance|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=5436144|work=[[NPR]]|date=27 May 2006|language=en|format=Audio interview}}</ref> Hudlin has said that the experience was formative, and led to his older brother attending [[Yale University]], and his attending [[Harvard University]].<ref name=HudlinEntertainment-About/> In 1979, Hudlin graduated from Assumption High School in East St. Louis.<ref name=StLouisAmerican-OscarNom-2013>{{cite news|title=Metro East native Reginald Hudlin receives Oscar nod for 'Django'|url=http://www.stlamerican.com/entertainment/living_it/metro-east-native-reginald-hudlin-receives-oscar-nod-for-django/article_a4377664-5bfa-11e2-83ac-001a4bcf887a.html|work=[[The St. Louis American]]|date=11 January 2013|language=en}}</ref>\n\nWhile an undergraduate at [[Harvard University]], Hudlin directed his thesis project, a short film called ''House Party,'' which went on to receive numerous awards including first place at the Black American Cinema Society Awards.<ref name=LATimes-BACS-Award-HouseParty-1986>{{cite news|last1=Thomas|first1=Kevin|title=Winning Black Videos, Films Highlight Youth|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1986-01-27/entertainment/ca-762_1_directors-guild|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=27 January 1986}}</ref> The film was inspired by his experience growing up in East St. Louis. In 1983, Hudlin graduated [[magna cum laude]] from Harvard with a B.A. in Visual and Environmental Studies.<ref name=HudlinEntertainment-About>{{cite news|title=The Reginald Hudlin Story|url=http://hudlinentertainment.com/about-me/the-reginald-hudlin-story/|work=Hudlin Entertainment|language=en}}</ref> His short film thesis was the basis for his first feature film, ''[[House Party (film)|House Party]].''<ref name=TooShortsBoombox-Podcast-2017>{{cite news|last1=$hort|first1=Too|last2=Loco|first2=Bobby|title=Writer / Director Reginald Hudlin|url=https://www.podcastone.com/episode/Writer-/-Director-Reginald-Hudlin-1718434-1|work=Too $hort's Boombox|publisher=PodcastOne|date=8 March 2017|format=Audio podcast}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nAfter college, Hudlin and his brother formed a production company and made music videos for such artists as [[Heavy D]], [[Jamaica Boys]], and others.<ref name=BlackDirectorsInHollywood-2003/>{{rp|234}} They were responsible for making the classic \"Hey Love\" 1980s-era TV commercial for a various-artists record, that played regularly on late night TV.<ref name=NPR-FreshAir-Boomerang-1992>{{cite news|last1=Gross|first1=Terry|title=Fresh Air with Terry Gross, July 10, 1992: Interview with Warrington Hudlin and Reginald Hudlin|url=http://39ea54ff11b298f9bcaa-1b99eba380497722926169d6da8b098e.r2.cf5.rackcdn.com/1992/FA19920710.mp3|work=[[Fresh Air]]|publisher=[[NPR]]|date=10 July 1992|format=Audio, starts at 36:13|oclc=971502139}}</ref><ref name=HeyLove-TVCommercial>{{cite web|title=\"Hey Love\" 1980s TV Commercial - No My Brother|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8AqVtTVbZms|date=1980s}}</ref>\n\nHudlin directed\u2014with older brother Warrington producing\u2014his first feature-length film, 1990's low-budget teen hip-hop comedy ''[[House Party (film)|House Party]],'' which starred [[Kid 'n Play]]. One of the messages of the film was its promotion of safe sex. The film, distributed by [[New Line Cinema]], was, according to ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'', one of the most profitable films of the decade.<ref name=LATimes-HousePartyEconomics-2000>{{cite news|last1=Hudlin|first1=Reginald|title=If It's a Question of Money . . .|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2000/sep/10/entertainment/ca-18434|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=10 September 2000}}</ref> New Line wanted to make sequels, but the Hudlins did not feel the compensation or deals were adequate.<ref name=BlackFilmmakersMagic-2003>{{cite book|last1=Alexander|first1=George|title=Why We Make Movies: Black Filmmakers Talk About the Magic of Cinema|date=2003|publisher=Harlem Moon|location=New York|isbn=978-0-307-41959-0|chapter=Reginald Hudlin|oclc=53445264}}</ref>{{rp|446}}\n\nHudlin went on to direct 1992's ''[[Boomerang (1992 film)|Boomerang]],'' again with older brother Warrington producing. The film was a big-budget romantic comedy that starred [[Eddie Murphy]], who had a term deal at [[Paramount Pictures]] and hired the Hudlin Brothers because he liked ''House Party.'' It starred an all-black cast that included [[Robin Givens]], [[Halle Berry]], [[Martin Lawrence]], [[David Alan Grier]], and [[Chris Rock]].<ref name=NPR-FreshAir-Boomerang-1992 /><ref name=NYTimes-Boomerang-EddieMurphy-1992>{{cite news|last1=Dowd|first1=Maureen|title=FILM; He's Never Been Happier, or More Glum|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/06/28/movies/film-he-s-never-been-happier-or-more-glum.html?pagewanted=all|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=28 June 1992}}</ref> ''Boomerang'' was based on an original idea by Murphy and was written by ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'' writers [[Barry W. Blaustein]] and [[David Sheffield]].<ref name=BlackFilm-Boomerang-2012>{{cite news|last1=Morales|first1=Wilson|title=Exclusive: Director Reginald Hudlin talks Boomerang 20 Years Later, Black Panther, and producing Django Unchained|url=http://www.blackfilm.com/read/2012/07/director-reginald-hudlin-talks-boomerang-20-years-later-black-panther-django-unchained/|work=BlackFilm.com|date=1 July 2012}}</ref>\n\nA celebration of the 25th anniversary of ''Boomerang's'' release was held on July 1, 2017, at the [[National Museum of African American History and Culture]] in Washington, D.C., with a conversation between Hudlin and producer George Alexander.<ref name=NMAAH-Boomerang25-2017>{{cite news|last1=House|first1=Jermaine|last2=Hernandez|first2=Shrita|title=African Americans and the Advertising Industry Series Leads the National Museum of African American History and Culture July Programming|url=https://nmaahc.si.edu/sites/default/files/downloads/news/july_2017_public_programs_release_17.374.pdf|work=[[National Museum of African American History and Culture]]|date=29 June 2017|format=Press release}}</ref><ref name=FKBOnline-Boomerang25-2017>{{cite news|last1=Ekokobe|first1=Reggie|title=Exclusive: Director Reginald Hudlin talks \"Boomerang\" 25 Years Later, \"Marshall,\" and More|url=http://fkbonline.com/exclusive-director-reginald-hudlin-talks-boomerang-25-years-later-marshall-and-more/|work=First Klass Breakfast|date=1 July 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 1992, while making ''Boomerang,'' Hudlin directed the first Black animated film, ''[[B\u00e9b\u00e9's Kids]]'', which was championed by Paramount's [[Brandon Tartikoff]], and was made in memory of comedian [[Robin Harris]], who had died in 1990.<ref name=BlackFilm-Boomerang-2012 />\n\nIn 1994, the Hudlin Brothers produced the [[HBO]] anthology multi-ethnic horror series ''Cosmic Slop'', of which Hudlin directed the episode \"[[The Space Traders]].\"  It was an adaptation of a [[Derrick Bell]] short story found in his book ''Faces at the Bottom of the Well: The Permanence of Racism.''<ref name=NYTimes-CosmicSlop-1994>{{cite news|last1=Meisler|first1=Andy|title=Using Fun to Show Blacks to Whites|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1994/11/07/arts/using-fun-to-show-blacks-to-whites.html|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=7 November 1994}}</ref><ref name=FacesAtBottomWell-SpaceTrader-1992>{{cite book|last1=Bell|first1=Derrick|title=Faces at the Bottom of the Well: The Permanence of Racism|date=1992|publisher=BasicBooks|location=New York, NY|isbn=978-0-786-72323-2|pages=158\u2013194|chapter=Chapter 9: The Space Trader|oclc=904402741}}</ref>\n\nHe went on to direct ''[[The Great White Hype]]'', ''[[The Ladies Man (2000 film)|The Ladies Man]]'', ''[[Serving Sara]]'' (2002), two episodes of the TV series ''[[Modern Family]]'', an episode of ''[[The Office (U.S. TV series)|The Office]]'', an episode of ''[[The Middle (TV series)|The Middle]]'', and several episodes of ''[[Outsourced (TV series)|Outsourced]]''.  He was also a recurring producer and director of ''[[The Bernie Mac Show]]'' for three years.\n\nFrom 2005 to 2008, Hudlin was the President of Entertainment for [[Black Entertainment Television|BET]]. Notable shows shepherded by Hudlin at that time included the documentary series ''[[American Gangster (TV series)|American Gangster]]'' and ''[[Sunday Best (American TV series)|Sunday Best]],'' a gospel-music singing-competition show. Hudlin created ''[[The BET Honors]]'' and the ''[[BET Hip Hop Awards]].''{{citation needed|date=September 2017}}\n\nDuring the time that he was President of BET, Hudlin wrote many of the [[Marvel Comics]] series ''[[Black Panther (comics)|Black Panther]]'' from 2005 to 2008, most notable for the 2006 storyline \"Bride of the Panther,\" which saw the character marry X-Men leader [[Storm (Marvel Comics)|Storm]].{{citation needed|date=September 2017}}\n\nHudlin was one of the producers of [[Quentin Tarantino]]'s ''[[Django Unchained]]'', starring [[Jamie Foxx]], [[Leonardo DiCaprio]], [[Christoph Waltz]], [[Kerry Washington]], and [[Samuel L. Jackson]]. On January 10, 2013, Hudlin received an [[Academy Awards|Oscar]] nomination for [[Academy Award for Best Picture|Best Picture]] for the film.<ref name=IndieWire-Django-OscarNom-2013>{{cite news|last1=Dowell|first1=Masha|title=Interview: Reginald Hudlin On His Oscar Journey, Working w/ RZA, Directing Again, More|url=http://www.indiewire.com/2013/02/interview-reginald-hudlin-on-his-oscar-journey-working-w-rza-directing-again-more-233596/|work=[[IndieWire]]|date=14 February 2013|language=en}}</ref>\n\nSince 2013, Hudlin has executive-produced the ''[[NAACP Image Award]]s.'' The show attained its highest rating on NBC in 2013, then became the highest-rated show in the history of [[TV One (U.S. TV network)|TV One]] in 2014. Hudlin produced a number of TV specials, including the ''[[88th Academy Awards]],'' hosted by [[Chris Rock]].{{citation needed|date=September 2017}}\n\nIn 2015, it was announced that Hudlin and artists [[Denys Cowan]] and [[Derek Dingle]] would be part of the relaunch of [[Milestone Media]], the comic book company founded by [[Dwayne McDuffie]], [[Denys Cowan]], and [[Derek Dingle]].<ref name=WashPost-MilestoneMedia-2015>{{cite news|last1=Betancourt|first1=David|title=EXCLUSIVE: Milestone Media rises again. Hudlin, Cowan and Dingle will revive company with eye toward characters of color|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/comic-riffs/wp/2015/01/21/exclusive-milestone-media-rises-again-hudlin-cowan-and-dingle-will-revive-company-with-eye-toward-characters-of-color/|work=[[The Washington Post]]|date=21 January 2015}}</ref><ref name=Indiewire-Milestone-2015>{{cite news|last1=Obenson|first1=Tambay A.|title=Watch: Reginald Hudlin and Denys Cowan Talk Milestone 2.0 {{!}} IndieWire|url=http://www.indiewire.com/2015/08/watch-reginald-hudlin-and-denys-cowan-talk-milestone-2-0-235019/|work=[[Indiewire]]|date=4 August 2015|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Hudlin produced the ''Black Movie Soundtrack'' celebration of Black music in movies, held at Los Angeles' [[Hollywood Bowl]], and hosted by [[Craig Robinson (actor)|Craig Robinson]]. ''Black Movie Soundtrack II'', also hosted by Robinson, was held in 2016.<ref name=HReporter-BlackMovieSoundtrackII-2016>{{cite news|last1=Gardner|first1=Chris|title=Oscar Producer Plans Second 'Black Movie Soundtrack' at the Hollywood Bowl|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/rambling-reporter/black-movie-soundtrack-returns-hollywood-868495|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=25 February 2016|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2017, it was announced that Hudlin would be directing an upcoming movie based on the comic ''[[Shadowman (comics)|Shadowman]]''.<ref name=HReporter-Shadowman-2017>{{cite news|last1=McMillan|first1=Graeme|title=Reginald Hudlin to Direct Valiant's Supernatural Superhero Movie 'Shadowman' (Exclusive)|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/reginald-hudlin-direct-valiants-supernatural-superhero-movie-shadowman-1012174|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=13 June 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2017, Hudlin's film, ''[[Marshall (film)|Marshall]]'', about [[Thurgood Marshall]], the first African-American Supreme Court justice, starring [[Chadwick Boseman]], was released.<ref name=FKBOnline-Boomerang25-2017 /> The screenplay was penned by Michael Koskoff and Jacob Koskoff, and co-stars [[Josh Gad]]. The film was made in [[Buffalo, New York|Buffalo]], [[New York (state)|New York]].<ref name=Deadline-Marshall-OpenRoad-2016>{{cite news|last1=Hipes|first1=Patrick|title=Open Road Acquires Thurgood Marshall Biopic Starring Chadwick Boseman|url=http://deadline.com/2016/06/marshall-movie-chadwick-boseman-open-road-1201769820/|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=9 June 2016}}</ref>\n\nHudlin contributed a story to the ''[[Black Panther (comics)|Black Panther]] Annual'' #1, released in February 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.avclub.com/iconic-creators-return-to-wakanda-in-this-black-panther-1823047658|title=Iconic creators return to Wakanda in this ''Black Panther Annual'' exclusive|last=Sava|first=Oliver|date= February 15, 2018|work=The A.V. Club|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180613015133/https://www.avclub.com/iconic-creators-return-to-wakanda-in-this-black-panther-1823047658 |archivedate= June 13, 2018|url-status= live|df= mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2019, it was announced that Hudlin was directing an upcoming film produced by [[Walt Disney Pictures]], titled ''[[Safety (upcoming film)|Safety]]'', which would be released on [[Disney+]].\n\n== Personal life ==\nIn 2002, Hudlin married Chrisette Hudlin (n\u00e9e Suter), a public relations consultant, in [[Montego Bay, Jamaica|Montego Bay]], [[Jamaica]].<ref name=Variety-Marriage-2003>{{cite news|last1=Variety Staff|title=Chrisette Suter and Reginald Hudlin|url=https://variety.com/2003/scene/people-news/chrisette-suter-and-reginald-hudlin-1117878266/|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=6 January 2003}}</ref><ref name=Essence-KamalaHarris-2016>{{cite news|last1=Owens|first1=Donna M.|title=California Attorney General Kamala Harris Plans to be America's Next Black Female Senator|url=http://www.essence.com/2016/01/13/california-attorney-general-kamala-harris-americas-next-black-female-senator|work=[[Essence (magazine)|Essence]]|date=13 January 2016}}</ref> They have two children.<ref name=HudlinEnt-Top10Heroes-2016>{{cite web|last1=Hudlin|first1=Reginald|title=Top Ten Heroes of the Year|url=http://hudlinentertainment.com/top-ten-heroes-of-the-year/|website=HudlinEntertainment.com|language=en|date=2016}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n;Films\n* 1983: ''House Party'' (Short) \u2013 Director, Writer\n* 1985: ''Reggie's World of Soul'' (Short) \u2013 Director<ref name=BlackDirectorsInHollywood-2003 />{{rp|234}}\n* 1986: ''The Kold Waves'' (Short) \u2013 Director<ref name=BlackDirectorsInHollywood-2003 />{{rp|234}}\n* 1986: ''[[She's Gotta Have It]]'' \u2013 Actor as Dog 4\n* 1990: ''[[House Party (film)|House Party]]'' \u2013 Director, Writer, Actor as Burglar #1\n* 1992: ''[[Boomerang (1992 film)|Boomerang]]'' \u2013 Director, Actor as Street Hustler\n* 1992: ''[[B\u00e9b\u00e9's Kids]]'' (Animated) \u2013 Executive Producer, Writer, Soundtrack: 3 songs: \"I Ain't Havin' It\", \"Freedom Song\", \"Straight Jackin'\"\n* 1993: ''[[Posse (1993 film)|Posse]]'' \u2013 Actor as Reporter 31\n* 1996: ''[[Joe's Apartment]]'' \u2013 Actor as Rodney Roach (voice)\n* 1996: ''[[The Great White Hype]]'' \u2013 Director\n* 1998: ''[[Ride (1998 film)|Ride]]'' \u2013 Producer\n* 2000: ''[[The Ladies Man (2000 film)|The Ladies Man]]'' \u2013 Director, Actor as Aloysius\n* 2002: ''[[Serving Sara]]'' \u2013 Director\n* 2012: ''[[Django Unchained]]'' \u2013 Producer\n* 2017: ''[[Burning Sands (2017 film)|Burning Sands]]'' \u2013 Producer\n* 2017: ''[[Blazing Samurai]]'' (Animated) \u2013 Executive Producer\n* 2017: ''[[Marshall (film)|Marshall]]'' \u2013 Producer, Director\n* 2019: ''[[The Black Godfather (2019 film)|The Black Godfather]]'' \u2013 Director\n* TBA: ''[[Shadowman (comics)#Film|Shadowman]]'' \u2013 Director<ref name=HReporter-Shadowman-2017 />\n;TV movies\n* 1994: ''Cosmic Slop'' \u2013 Executive Producer, Director (segment: \"Space Traders\")\n;TV specials\n* 1994: ''The Last Days of Russell'' \u2013 Co-Executive Producer, Director, Writer\n* 2005: ''[[Richard Pryor: The Funniest Man Dead or Alive]]'' (TV documentary) \u2013 Executive Producer, Director\n* 2006: ''Bring That Year Back 2006: Laugh Now, Cry Later'' \u2013 Network Executive Producer\n* 2006: ''[[BET Hip Hop Awards]]'' \u2013 Executive in Charge of Production\n* 2008: ''[[The BET Honors]]'' \u2013 Executive in Charge of Production\n* 2010: ''Burr and Hart'' \u2013 Director\n* 2013: ''[[44th NAACP Image Awards]]'' \u2013 Executive Producer\n* 2014: ''[[Governors Awards]]'' \u2013 Executive Producer\n* 2014: ''[[45th NAACP Image Awards]]'' \u2013 Executive Producer\n* 2015: ''[[46th NAACP Image Awards]]'' \u2013 Executive Producer\n* 2016: ''[[47th NAACP Image Awards]]'' \u2013 Executive Producer\n* 2016: ''[[88th Academy Awards]]'' \u2013 Producer\n* 2016: ''[[Showtime at the Apollo]]'' \u2013 Executive Producer\n* 2017: ''[[48th NAACP Image Awards]]'' \u2013 Executive Producer\n; TV series\n* 2000: ''[[City of Angels (2000 TV series)|City of Angels]]'' \u2013 Director (1 episode)\n* 2002-2005: ''[[The Bernie Mac Show]]'' \u2013 Producer (7 episodes), Director (11 episodes)\n* 2005: ''[[Everybody Hates Chris]]'' \u2013 Director (1 episode)\n* 2005-2008: ''[[The Boondocks (TV series)|The Boondocks]]'' \u2013 Executive Producer (31 episodes)\n* 2006: ''Somebodies'' \u2013 Executive in Charge of Co-Productions\n* 2007: ''Wifey'' \u2013 Director\n* 2008: ''[[Brothers to Brutha]]'' \u2013 Network Executive\n* 2008-2013: ''BET's Comicview'' \u2013 President of Entertainment (21 episodes)\n* 2009: ''[[Raising the Bar (2008 TV series)|Raising the Bar]]'' \u2013 Director (1 episode)\n* 2009: ''[[The Office (U.S. TV series)|The Office]]'' \u2013 Director (1 episode)\n* 2009: ''[[The Middle (TV series)|The Middle]]'' \u2013 Director (1 episode)\n* 2009-2010: ''[[Modern Family (TV series)|Modern Family]]'' \u2013 Director (2 episodes)\n* 2010: ''[[Better Off Ted]]'' \u2013 Director (1 episode)\n* 2010: ''[[Sons of Tucson]]'' \u2013 Director (1 episode)\n* 2010: ''[[Black Panther (TV series)|Marvel's Black Panther]]'' \u2013 Executive Producer (1 episode), Writer (1 episode), Actor as President (voice) in Episode #1.6\n* 2010-2011: ''[[Outsourced (TV series)|Outsourced]]'' \u2013 Director (2 episodes\n* 2010-2012: ''[[Psych]]'' \u2013 Director (2 episodes)\n* 2011: ''[[Friends with Benefits (TV series)|Friends with Benefits]]'' \u2013 Director (1 episode)\n* 2012: ''[[Are We There Yet? (TV series)|Are We There Yet?]]'' \u2013 Director (3 episodes)\n* 2013: ''[[Bones (TV series)|Bones]]'' \u2013 Director (1 episode)\n* 2013: ''[[How to Live with Your Parents (For the Rest of Your Life)]]'' \u2013 Director (1 episode)\n* 2013: ''[[House Party: Tonight's the Night]]'' \u2013 Writer, based on characters created by (1 episode)\n* 2014-2015: ''[[Bad Judge]]'' \u2013 Director (2 episodes)\n* 2014-2015: ''[[Marry Me (U.S. TV series)|Marry Me]]'' \u2013 Director (2 episodes)\n* 2014-2015: ''[[Murder in the First (TV series)|Murder in the First]]'' \u2013 Director (3 episodes)\n* 2015: ''[[Weird Loners]]'' \u2013 Director (1 episode)\n* 2015: ''[[New Girl]]'' \u2013 Director (1 episode)\n* 2015: ''[[Telenovela (TV series)|Telenovela]]'' \u2013 Director (1 episode)\n* 2016: ''[[Heartbeat (2016 TV series)|Heartbeat]]'' \u2013 Director (1 episode)\n* 2016: ''[[Angel from Hell]]'' \u2013 Director (1 episode)\n* 2016: ''[[Uncle Buck (2016 TV series)|Uncle Buck]]'' \u2013 Director (2 episodes)\n* 2017: ''Blue & Green'' \u2013 Executive Producer \n* 2019: ''[[Black Monday (TV series)|Black Monday]]'' - Director (2 episodes)\n* 2019: ''[[The Last O.G.]]'' - Director (3 episodes)\n\n== Awards ==\n* 1986: Black American Cinema Society (film archives of the Western States Black Research Center), Black Independent Video and Film-maker's Awards, $1,500 first prize for ''House Party'' (short)<ref name=LATimes-BACS-Award-HouseParty-1986 />\n* 1990: [[Sundance Film Festival]], Filmmakers Trophy for ''[[House Party (film)|House Party]]''\n* 1990: [[Sundance Film Festival]], Grand Jury Prize for ''[[House Party (film)|House Party]]'' \u2013 nominee\n* 1990: [[Deauville Film Festival]], Critics Award for ''[[House Party (film)|House Party]]'' \u2013 nominee\n* 1991: [[Film Independent Spirit Award]], Best First Feature for ''[[House Party (film)|House Party]]'' \u2013 nominee\n* 1991: [[Film Independent Spirit Award]], Best Director for ''[[House Party (film)|House Party]]'' \u2013 nominee\n* 1995: [[CableACE]], Dramatic or Theatrical Special for ''Cosmic Slop''\n* 2012: [[American Film Institute Awards 2012]] for ''[[Django Unchained]]'', Top 10 Films\n* 2013: [[Academy Award for Best Picture]] for ''[[Django Unchained]]'' \u2013 nominee<ref name=IndieWire-Django-OscarNom-2013 />\n* 2013: [[Golden Globe Award for Best Motion Picture \u2013 Drama]] for ''[[Django Unchained]]'' \u2013 nominee<ref name=GoldenGlobeNom-Django-2013>{{cite web|title=Winners & Nominees 2013|url=http://www.goldenglobes.com/winners-nominees/2013|website=[[Golden Globe Award]]|language=en|date=2013}}</ref>\n* 2013: [[PGA Awards]], Outstanding Producer of Theatrical Motion Pictures for ''[[Django Unchained]]'' \u2013 nominee\n* 2015: [[Comic Con]], Icon Award<ref name=ComicCon-IconAward-2015>{{cite news|title=Reginald Hudlin and Joss Whedon Are the Latest Comic-Con Icon Award Recipients!|url=https://www.comic-con.org/toucan/reginald-hudlin-and-joss-whedon-are-latest-comic-con-icon-award-recipients|work=[[Comic-Con International]]: San Diego|date=29 July 2015|language=en}}</ref>\n* 2016: [[African-American Film Critics Association]], Salute to Excellence Award<ref name=HReporter-AAFCA-2015>{{cite news|last1=Galuppo|first1=Mia|title=Oscars Producer Reginald Hudlin to be Honored at AAFCA Awards|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/oscars-producer-reginald-hudlin-be-849243|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=15 December 2015|language=en}}</ref>\n* 2016: [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Special Class Program]] for ''[[88th Academy Awards]]'' \u2013 nominee\n\n== Leadership and membership ==\n* [[UCLA School of Theater, Film and Television]], Board Member<ref name=UCLA-BoardMember-2017>{{cite news|title=Executive Board - Reginald Hudlin|url=http://www.tft.ucla.edu/about/executive-board/reginald-hudlin/|work=[[UCLA School of Theater, Film and Television]]|date=2017}}</ref>\n* [[Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences]], Board of Governors\n\n== Works and publications ==\n; Graphic novels\n* {{cite book|last1=McGruder|first1=Aaron|last2=Hudlin|first2=Reginald|last3=Baker|first3=Kyle (illustrations)|title=Birth of a Nation: A Comic Novel|url=https://archive.org/details/birthofnationcom00mcgr|url-access=registration|date=2004|publisher=Crown Publishers|location=New York|isbn=978-1-400-08316-9|oclc=54857618}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Hudlin|first1=Reginald (writer)|last2=Romita Jr.|first2=John (penciler)|last3=Janson|first3=Klaus (inker)|last4=White|first4=Dean (colors)|title=Black Panther: Who is the Black Panther|date=2005|publisher=Marvel|location=New York|isbn=978-0-785-11748-3|oclc=780282040}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Hudlin|first1=Reginald (writer)|last2=Tan|first2=Billy (pencils)|last3=Buckingham|first3=Mark (pencils)|title=Marvel Knights Spider-Man [Vol. 04], Wild Blue Yonder|date=2005|publisher=Marvel Comics|location=New York|isbn=978-0-785-11761-2|oclc=830159672}} \u2013 Contains material originally published in magazine form as Marvel Knights Spider-man #13-18\n* {{cite book|last1=David|first1=Peter|last2=Straczynski|first2=J. Michael|last3=Hudlin|first3=Reginald|last4=Wieringo|first4=Mike (artist)|last5=Deodato|first5=Mike (artist)|last6=Lee|first6=Pat (artist)|title=Spider-Man: The Other|date=2006|publisher=Marvel Pub.|location=New York|isbn=978-0-785-12188-6|oclc=62714568}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Hudlin|first1=Reginald (writer)|last2=Eaton|first2=Scot (pencils)|title=Black Panther: The Bride|date=2006|publisher=Marvel|location=New York|isbn=978-0-785-12107-7|edition=Direct|oclc=948817543}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Hudlin|first1=Reginald (writer)|last2=Eaton|first2=Scot (penciler)|last3=Garcia|first3=Manuel (penciler)|last4=Turnbull|first4=Koi (penciler)|last5=To|first5=Marcus (penciler)|title=Black Panther: Civil War|date=2007|publisher=Marvel|location=New York, NY|isbn=978-0-785-12235-7|oclc=144224099}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Hudlin|first1=Reginald (writer)|last2=Portela|first2=Francis (pencils)|title=Black Panther: Four the Hard Way|date=2007|publisher=Marvel|location=New York|isbn=978-0-785-12655-3|oclc=751756495}} \u2013 Contains material originally published in single magazine form as: Black Panther #26-30\n* {{cite book|last1=Hudlin|first1=Reginald (writer)|last2=Portela|first2=Francis (penciler)|last3=Rodriguez|first3=Carlos (penciler)|last4=Sharpe|first4=Kevin (penciler)|last5=Cafu (penciler)|last6=Portela|first6=Francis (inks)|last7=Hennessy|first7=Bit & Andrew (inks)|last8=Staples|first8=Val (colors)|title=Black Panther: Back to Africa|date=2008|publisher=Marvel|location=New York|isbn=978-0-785-12452-8|oclc=540015636}} \u2013 Also includes ''Black Panther: Black to the Future''\n** {{cite book|last1=Hudlin|first1=Reginald (writer)|last2=Stroman|first2=Larry (pencils)|last3=Lashley|first3=Ken (pencils)|last4=Paris|first4=Roland (inks)|last5=Cuevas|first5=Carlos (inks)|last6=Sibal|first6=Jon (inks)|last7=Milla|first7=Matt (colors)|last8=Staples|first8=Val (colors)|last9=Petit|first9=Cory (letters)|title=Black Panther: Black to the Future|date=2008|publisher=Marvel|location=New York|isbn=978-0-785-12452-8|oclc=540015636}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Hudlin|first1=Reginald (writer)|last2=Portela|first2=Francis (art)|title=Black Panther: Little Green Men|date=2008|publisher=Marvel|location=New York|isbn=978-0-785-12657-7|oclc=191890888}} \u2013 Contains material originally published in magazine form as Black Panther #31-34\n* {{cite book|last1=Hudlin|first1=Reginald (writer)|last2=Neary|first2=Paul (inks)|last3=Lashley|first3=Ken (pencils)|title=Black Panther: The Deadliest of the Species|date=2009|publisher=Marvel|location=New York|isbn=978-0-785-13342-1|oclc=765104721}} \u2013 Collecting Black Panther #1-6\n* {{cite book|last1=Hudlin|first1=Reginald (writer)|last2=Cowan|first2=Denys (pencils)|title=Captain America/Black Panther: Flags of Our Fathers|date=2010|publisher=Marvel Worldwide|location=New York|isbn=978-0-785-14401-4|oclc=780283834}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Maberry|first1=Jonathan (writer)|last2=Hudlin|first2=Reginald (writer)|last3=Conrad|first3=Will (art)|title=Black Panther: Power|date=2010|publisher=Marvel|location=New York|isbn=978-0-785-13861-7|oclc=437299872}} \u2013 Contains material originally published in magazine form as Black Panther #7-12\n* {{cite book|last1=Tarantino|first1=Quentin (adapted from the original screenplay by)|last2=Hudlin|first2=Reginald (adaptation)|last3=Gu\u00e9ra|first3=R.M. (art by)|last4=Latour|first4=Jason (art by)|last5=Cowan|first5=Denys (art by)|last6=\u017de\u017eelj|first6=Danijel (art by)|last7=Floyd|first7=John (art by)|title=Django Unchained|date=2014|publisher=Vertigo|location=New York|isbn=978-1-401-24709-6|oclc=877860979}} \u2013 Originally published in single magazine form in DJANGO UNCHAINED 1-7\n* {{cite book|last1=Maberry|first1=Jonathan (writer)|last2=Hudlin|first2=Reginald (writer|last3=Conrad|first3=Will (artist)|last4=Eaton|first4=Scot (artist)|last5=Moll|first5=Shawn (artist)|last6=Gugliotta|first6=Gianluca (artist)|title=Black Panther: Doomwar|date=2017|publisher=Marvel Worldwide, Inc.|location=New York|isbn=978-1-302-90416-6|oclc=951950784}} \u2013 Contains material originally published in magazine form as Doomwar #1-6\n; Selected writing\n* {{cite news|last1=Hudlin|first1=Reginald|title=If It's a Question of Money . . .|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2000/sep/10/entertainment/ca-18434|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=10 September 2000}}\n* {{cite news|last1=Hudlin|first1=Reginald|title='Django Unchained' Producer on 'Selma' Oscar Snubs: Did Voters Have \"Racial Fatigue\"? (Guest Column)|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/django-unchained-producer-selma-oscar-764888|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=21 January 2015|language=en}}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Warrington Hudlin]]\n* ''[[Black Panther (comics)|Black Panther]]''\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{cite book|last1=Alexander|first1=George|title=Why We Make Movies: Black Filmmakers Talk About the Magic of Cinema|date=2003|publisher=Harlem Moon|location=New York|isbn=978-0-307-41959-0|chapter=Reginald Hudlin|oclc=53445264}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Donalson|first1=Melvin Burke|title=Black Directors in Hollywood|date=2003|publisher=University of Texas Press|location=Austin|isbn=978-0-292-79875-5|pages=204\u2013277|chapter=Chapter 9: Not Without Laughter: Directors of Comedy and Romance, Chapter 10: Off the Hook: Comedy and Romance with a Hip-Hop Flavor|oclc=55731956}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Gates, Jr.|first1=Henry Louis|title=America Behind the Color Line: Dialogues with African Americans|date=2005|publisher=Warner Books|location=New York|isbn=978-0-446-69390-5|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yE5Rw7PkupAC&lpg=PT17&dq=oclc669069221&as_brr=3&as_pt=BOOKS&pg=PT233#v=onepage&q=hudlin&f=false|chapter=Independent Means: Reginald Hudlin|oclc=57551433|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/americabehindcol00henr}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Eichenbaum|first1=Rose|editor1-last=Hirt-Manheimer|editor1-first=Aron|title=The Director Within: Storytellers of Stage and Screen|date=2014|publisher=Wesleyan University Press|location=Middletown, CT|isbn=978-0-819-57494-7|pages=82\u201390|chapter=Reginald Hudlin|oclc=893600248}}\n* {{cite web|last1=Hudlin Entertainment|title=SDCC 2015 Spotlight On Reginald Hudlin: Part 1|url=https://vimeo.com/137902863|website=[[Comic-Con International]]|format=Video|date=31 August 2015}} [https://vimeo.com/137903676 \"Part 2\"]. [https://vimeo.com/137904943 \"Part 3\"]. [https://vimeo.com/137905624 \"Part 4\"]. [https://vimeo.com/137907116 \"Part 5\"].\n\n==External links==\n{{Commonscategory}}\n* [http://hudlinentertainment.com Hudlin Entertainment]\n* [http://reggiesworld.com Reggie's World]\n* {{IMDb name|0399737}}\n* {{gcdb|type=credit|search=Reginald+Hudlin|title=Reginald Hudlin}}\n* {{comicbookdb|type=creator|id=2298|title=Reginald Hudlin}}\n\n{{Reginald Hudlin}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hudlin, Reginald}}\n[[Category:1961 births]]\n[[Category:African-American comics creators]]\n[[Category:American comics creators]]\n[[Category:African-American film directors]]\n[[Category:African-American television directors]]\n[[Category:American comics writers]]\n[[Category:American television directors]]\n[[Category:Harvard University alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Centreville, Illinois]]\n[[Category:Film directors from Illinois]]\n[[Category:Phi Beta Sigma Brothers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American filmmaker}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Reginald Hudlin\n| image        = 10.5.17ReginaldHudlinByLuigiNovi1.jpg\n| alt          = Reginald Hudlin\n| caption      = Hudlin at the 2017 [[New York Comic Con]]\n| birth_name   = Reginald Alan Hudlin\n| birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1961|12|15}}\n| birth_place  = [[Centreville, Illinois]], U.S.\n| nationality  = [[United States|American]]\n| other_names  = Reggie Hudlin\n| occupation   = Film director<br/>Writer<br/>Producer\n| years_active = 1983&ndash;present\n| known_for    = ''[[House Party (film)|House Party]]''<br/> ''[[Django Unchained]]'' \n| home_town    = [[East St. Louis, Illinois]], U.S.\n| spouse       = {{marriage|Chrisette Suter|November 30, 2002}}\n| children     = 2\n| relatives    = [[Warrington Hudlin]] (brother)\n}}\n'''Reginald Alan Hudlin''' (born December 15, 1961) is an American film screenwriter, director and producer.<ref name=BlackDirectorsInHollywood-2003>{{cite book|last1=Donalson|first1=Melvin Burke|title=Black Directors in Hollywood|date=2003|publisher=University of Texas Press|location=Austin|isbn=978-0-292-79875-5|chapter=Chapter 9: Not Without Laughter: Directors of Comedy and Romance, Chapter 10: Off the Hook: Comedy and Romance with a Hip-Hop Flavor|oclc=55731956}}</ref> Along with his older brother [[Warrington Hudlin]], he is known as one of the '''Hudlin Brothers.'''<ref name=FilmComment-HouseParty-1990>{{cite journal|last1=Hudlin|first1=Reginald|last2=Hudlin|first2=Warrington|last3=Glicksman|first3=Marlaine|title=They Gotta Have It|journal=[[Film Comment]]|date=May 1990|volume=26|issue=3|pages=65\u201369|jstor=43454842}} {{Closed access}}</ref> From 2005 to 2008, Hudlin was President of Entertainment for [[Black Entertainment Television|Black Entertainment Television (BET)]]. Hudlin has also written numerous graphic novels.<ref name=SilverBullet-Interview-2005>{{cite news|last1=Encarnacion|first1=Jonathan|title=Uncompromising Articulation: Reginald Hudlin|url=http://silverbulletcomics.com/news/story.php?a=321|work=[[Silver Bullet Comic Books]]|date=13 April 2005|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20051125211734/http://silverbulletcomics.com/news/story.php?a=321|archivedate=25 November 2005}}</ref> He co-produced the [[88th Academy Awards]] ceremony in 2016 as well as other TV specials. Hudlin's breakout film was 1990's ''[[House Party (film)|House Party]]'',<ref name=Cineaste-HouseParty-1990>{{cite journal|last1=Hudlin|first1=Reginald|last2=Hudlin|first2=Warrington|last3=Kantor|first3=Michael|title=Tearing the Roof Off the Sucker: An Interview with Reginald and Warrington Hudlin|journal=[[Cineaste (magazine)|Cin\u00e9aste]]|date=1990|volume=18|issue=1|pages=22\u201323|jstor=41687018}} {{Closed access}}</ref> and he worked as a producer on [[Quentin Tarantino]]'s 2012 film, ''[[Django Unchained]]'', which earned him an [[Academy Awards|Academy Award]] nomination for [[Academy Award for Best Picture|Best Picture]]. He also directed the 1992 film ''[[Boomerang (1992 film)|Boomerang]]''.\n\n== Early life ==\nHudlin was born in [[Centreville, Illinois]], the son of Helen Hudlin (n\u00e9e Cason), a teacher who worked in special education, and Warrington W. Hudlin, Sr., an insurance executive and educator.<ref name=BlackDirectorsInHollywood-2003 />{{rp|234}} Hudlin's older brother, [[Warrington Hudlin]], is also a film director, as well as an actor and producer. Hudlin is the youngest, with middle brother, Christopher Hudlin, working with their father in the insurance business.{{citation needed|date=September 2017}}\n\nThe Hudlins grew up in [[East St. Louis, Illinois|East St. Louis]], [[Illinois]], where the family had deep roots.<ref name=NYTimes-HouseParty-1990>{{cite news|last1=Greenberg|first1=James|title=In Hollywood, Black Is In|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1990/03/04/movies/in-hollywood-black-is-in.html|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=4 March 1990}}</ref> The Hudlin Brothers are paternal great-great-grandsons of Peter and Nancy Hudlin, who were part of the [[Underground Railroad]]. Their great uncle was an influential tennis instructor named Richard A. Hudlin, who mentored [[Arthur Ashe]] and [[Althea Gibson]].<ref name=StLouisPostDispatch-UndergroundRR-2000>{{cite news|last1=Franklin|first1=Donald E.|title=Its History Rides on the Underground Railroad|work=[[St. Louis Post-Dispatch]]|date=27 February 2000|location=St. Louis|page=C.1|issn=1930-9600|id={{ProQuest|40400223}}}} {{Closed access}}</ref>\n\nThe Hudlins attended [[Katherine Dunham]]'s [[Performing Arts Training Center|Center for the Performing Arts]], an experimental school, Warrington for high school and Reginald for after school martial arts classes.<ref name=NPR-Dunham-Obit-2006>{{cite news|last1=Elliott|first1=Debbie|last2=Dryden|first2=Jim|last3=Dunham|first3=Katherine|title=Katherine Dunham Helped Teach the World to Dance|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=5436144|work=[[NPR]]|date=27 May 2006|language=en|format=Audio interview}}</ref> Hudlin has said that the experience was formative, and led to his older brother attending [[Yale University]], and his attending [[Harvard University]].<ref name=HudlinEntertainment-About/> In 1979, Hudlin graduated from Assumption High School in East St. Louis.<ref name=StLouisAmerican-OscarNom-2013>{{cite news|title=Metro East native Reginald Hudlin receives Oscar nod for 'Django'|url=http://www.stlamerican.com/entertainment/living_it/metro-east-native-reginald-hudlin-receives-oscar-nod-for-django/article_a4377664-5bfa-11e2-83ac-001a4bcf887a.html|work=[[The St. Louis American]]|date=11 January 2013|language=en}}</ref>\n\nWhile an undergraduate at [[Harvard University]], Hudlin directed his thesis project, a short film called ''House Party,'' which went on to receive numerous awards including first place at the Black American Cinema Society Awards.<ref name=LATimes-BACS-Award-HouseParty-1986>{{cite news|last1=Thomas|first1=Kevin|title=Winning Black Videos, Films Highlight Youth|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1986-01-27/entertainment/ca-762_1_directors-guild|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=27 January 1986}}</ref> The film was inspired by his experience growing up in East St. Louis. In 1983, Hudlin graduated [[magna cum laude]] from Harvard with a B.A. in Visual and Environmental Studies.<ref name=HudlinEntertainment-About>{{cite news|title=The Reginald Hudlin Story|url=http://hudlinentertainment.com/about-me/the-reginald-hudlin-story/|work=Hudlin Entertainment|language=en}}</ref> His short film thesis was the basis for his first feature film, ''[[House Party (film)|House Party]].''<ref name=TooShortsBoombox-Podcast-2017>{{cite news|last1=$hort|first1=Too|last2=Loco|first2=Bobby|title=Writer / Director Reginald Hudlin|url=https://www.podcastone.com/episode/Writer-/-Director-Reginald-Hudlin-1718434-1|work=Too $hort's Boombox|publisher=PodcastOne|date=8 March 2017|format=Audio podcast}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nAfter college, Hudlin and his brother formed a production company and made music videos for such artists as [[Heavy D]], [[Jamaica Boys]], and others.<ref name=BlackDirectorsInHollywood-2003/>{{rp|234}} They were responsible for making the classic \"Hey Love\" 1980s-era TV commercial for a various-artists record, that played regularly on late night TV.<ref name=NPR-FreshAir-Boomerang-1992>{{cite news|last1=Gross|first1=Terry|title=Fresh Air with Terry Gross, July 10, 1992: Interview with Warrington Hudlin and Reginald Hudlin|url=http://39ea54ff11b298f9bcaa-1b99eba380497722926169d6da8b098e.r2.cf5.rackcdn.com/1992/FA19920710.mp3|work=[[Fresh Air]]|publisher=[[NPR]]|date=10 July 1992|format=Audio, starts at 36:13|oclc=971502139}}</ref><ref name=HeyLove-TVCommercial>{{cite web|title=\"Hey Love\" 1980s TV Commercial - No My Brother|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8AqVtTVbZms|date=1980s}}</ref>\n\nHudlin directed\u2014with older brother Warrington producing\u2014his first feature-length film, 1990's low-budget teen hip-hop comedy ''[[House Party (film)|House Party]],'' which starred [[Kid 'n Play]]. One of the messages of the film was its promotion of safe sex. The film, distributed by [[New Line Cinema]], was, according to ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'', one of the most profitable films of the decade.<ref name=LATimes-HousePartyEconomics-2000>{{cite news|last1=Hudlin|first1=Reginald|title=If It's a Question of Money . . .|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2000/sep/10/entertainment/ca-18434|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=10 September 2000}}</ref> New Line wanted to make sequels, but the Hudlins did not feel the compensation or deals were adequate.<ref name=BlackFilmmakersMagic-2003>{{cite book|last1=Alexander|first1=George|title=Why We Make Movies: Black Filmmakers Talk About the Magic of Cinema|date=2003|publisher=Harlem Moon|location=New York|isbn=978-0-307-41959-0|chapter=Reginald Hudlin|oclc=53445264}}</ref>{{rp|446}}\n\nHudlin went on to direct 1992's ''[[Boomerang (1992 film)|Boomerang]],'' again with older brother Warrington producing. The film was a big-budget romantic comedy that starred [[Eddie Murphy]], who had a term deal at [[Paramount Pictures]] and hired the Hudlin Brothers because he liked ''House Party.'' It starred an all-black cast that included [[Robin Givens]], [[Halle Berry]], [[Martin Lawrence]], [[David Alan Grier]], and [[Chris Rock]].<ref name=NPR-FreshAir-Boomerang-1992 /><ref name=NYTimes-Boomerang-EddieMurphy-1992>{{cite news|last1=Dowd|first1=Maureen|title=FILM; He's Never Been Happier, or More Glum|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/06/28/movies/film-he-s-never-been-happier-or-more-glum.html?pagewanted=all|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=28 June 1992}}</ref> ''Boomerang'' was based on an original idea by Murphy and was written by ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'' writers [[Barry W. Blaustein]] and [[David Sheffield]].<ref name=BlackFilm-Boomerang-2012>{{cite news|last1=Morales|first1=Wilson|title=Exclusive: Director Reginald Hudlin talks Boomerang 20 Years Later, Black Panther, and producing Django Unchained|url=http://www.blackfilm.com/read/2012/07/director-reginald-hudlin-talks-boomerang-20-years-later-black-panther-django-unchained/|work=BlackFilm.com|date=1 July 2012}}</ref>\n\nA celebration of the 25th anniversary of ''Boomerang's'' release was held on July 1, 2017, at the [[National Museum of African American History and Culture]] in Washington, D.C., with a conversation between Hudlin and producer George Alexander.<ref name=NMAAH-Boomerang25-2017>{{cite news|last1=House|first1=Jermaine|last2=Hernandez|first2=Shrita|title=African Americans and the Advertising Industry Series Leads the National Museum of African American History and Culture July Programming|url=https://nmaahc.si.edu/sites/default/files/downloads/news/july_2017_public_programs_release_17.374.pdf|work=[[National Museum of African American History and Culture]]|date=29 June 2017|format=Press release}}</ref><ref name=FKBOnline-Boomerang25-2017>{{cite news|last1=Ekokobe|first1=Reggie|title=Exclusive: Director Reginald Hudlin talks \"Boomerang\" 25 Years Later, \"Marshall,\" and More|url=http://fkbonline.com/exclusive-director-reginald-hudlin-talks-boomerang-25-years-later-marshall-and-more/|work=First Klass Breakfast|date=1 July 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 1992, while making ''Boomerang,'' Hudlin directed the first Black animated film, ''[[B\u00e9b\u00e9's Kids]]'', which was championed by Paramount's [[Brandon Tartikoff]], and was made in memory of comedian [[Robin Harris]], who had died in 1990.<ref name=BlackFilm-Boomerang-2012 />\n\nIn 1994, the Hudlin Brothers produced the [[HBO]] anthology multi-ethnic horror series ''Cosmic Slop'', of which Hudlin directed the episode \"[[The Space Traders]].\"  It was an adaptation of a [[Derrick Bell]] short story found in his book ''Faces at the Bottom of the Well: The Permanence of Racism.''<ref name=NYTimes-CosmicSlop-1994>{{cite news|last1=Meisler|first1=Andy|title=Using Fun to Show Blacks to Whites|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1994/11/07/arts/using-fun-to-show-blacks-to-whites.html|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=7 November 1994}}</ref><ref name=FacesAtBottomWell-SpaceTrader-1992>{{cite book|last1=Bell|first1=Derrick|title=Faces at the Bottom of the Well: The Permanence of Racism|date=1992|publisher=BasicBooks|location=New York, NY|isbn=978-0-786-72323-2|pages=158\u2013194|chapter=Chapter 9: The Space Trader|oclc=904402741}}</ref>\n\nHe went on to direct ''[[The Great White Hype]]'', ''[[The Ladies Man (2000 film)|The Ladies Man]]'', ''[[Serving Sara]]'' (2002), two episodes of the TV series ''[[Modern Family]]'', an episode of ''[[The Office (U.S. TV series)|The Office]]'', an episode of ''[[The Middle (TV series)|The Middle]]'', and several episodes of ''[[Outsourced (TV series)|Outsourced]]''.  He was also a recurring producer and director of ''[[The Bernie Mac Show]]'' for three years.\n\nFrom 2005 to 2008, Hudlin was the President of Entertainment for [[Black Entertainment Television|BET]]. Notable shows shepherded by Hudlin at that time included the documentary series ''[[American Gangster (TV series)|American Gangster]]'' and ''[[Sunday Best (American TV series)|Sunday Best]],'' a gospel-music singing-competition show. Hudlin created ''[[The BET Honors]]'' and the ''[[BET Hip Hop Awards]].''{{citation needed|date=September 2017}}\n\nDuring the time that he was President of BET, Hudlin wrote many of the [[Marvel Comics]] series ''[[Black Panther (comics)|Black Panther]]'' from 2005 to 2008, most notable for the 2006 storyline \"Bride of the Panther,\" which saw the character marry X-Men leader [[Storm (Marvel Comics)|Storm]].{{citation needed|date=September 2017}}\n\nHudlin was one of the producers of [[Quentin Tarantino]]'s ''[[Django Unchained]]'', starring [[Jamie Foxx]], [[Leonardo DiCaprio]], [[Christoph Waltz]], [[Kerry Washington]], and [[Samuel L. Jackson]]. On January 10, 2013, Hudlin received an [[Academy Awards|Oscar]] nomination for [[Academy Award for Best Picture|Best Picture]] for the film.<ref name=IndieWire-Django-OscarNom-2013>{{cite news|last1=Dowell|first1=Masha|title=Interview: Reginald Hudlin On His Oscar Journey, Working w/ RZA, Directing Again, More|url=http://www.indiewire.com/2013/02/interview-reginald-hudlin-on-his-oscar-journey-working-w-rza-directing-again-more-233596/|work=[[IndieWire]]|date=14 February 2013|language=en}}</ref>\n\nSince 2013, Hudlin has executive-produced the ''[[NAACP Image Award]]s.'' The show attained its highest rating on NBC in 2013, then became the highest-rated show in the history of [[TV One]] in 2014. Hudlin produced a number of TV specials, including the ''[[88th Academy Awards]],'' hosted by [[Chris Rock]].{{citation needed|date=September 2017}}\n\nIn 2015, it was announced that Hudlin and artists [[Denys Cowan]] and [[Derek Dingle]] would be part of the relaunch of [[Milestone Media]], the comic book company founded by [[Dwayne McDuffie]], [[Denys Cowan]], and [[Derek Dingle]].<ref name=WashPost-MilestoneMedia-2015>{{cite news|last1=Betancourt|first1=David|title=EXCLUSIVE: Milestone Media rises again. Hudlin, Cowan and Dingle will revive company with eye toward characters of color|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/comic-riffs/wp/2015/01/21/exclusive-milestone-media-rises-again-hudlin-cowan-and-dingle-will-revive-company-with-eye-toward-characters-of-color/|work=[[The Washington Post]]|date=21 January 2015}}</ref><ref name=Indiewire-Milestone-2015>{{cite news|last1=Obenson|first1=Tambay A.|title=Watch: Reginald Hudlin and Denys Cowan Talk Milestone 2.0 {{!}} IndieWire|url=http://www.indiewire.com/2015/08/watch-reginald-hudlin-and-denys-cowan-talk-milestone-2-0-235019/|work=[[Indiewire]]|date=4 August 2015|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Hudlin produced the ''Black Movie Soundtrack'' celebration of Black music in movies, held at Los Angeles' [[Hollywood Bowl]], and hosted by [[Craig Robinson (actor)|Craig Robinson]]. ''Black Movie Soundtrack II'', also hosted by Robinson, was held in 2016.<ref name=HReporter-BlackMovieSoundtrackII-2016>{{cite news|last1=Gardner|first1=Chris|title=Oscar Producer Plans Second 'Black Movie Soundtrack' at the Hollywood Bowl|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/rambling-reporter/black-movie-soundtrack-returns-hollywood-868495|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=25 February 2016|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2017, it was announced that Hudlin would be directing an upcoming movie based on the comic ''[[Shadowman (comics)|Shadowman]]''.<ref name=HReporter-Shadowman-2017>{{cite news|last1=McMillan|first1=Graeme|title=Reginald Hudlin to Direct Valiant's Supernatural Superhero Movie 'Shadowman' (Exclusive)|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/reginald-hudlin-direct-valiants-supernatural-superhero-movie-shadowman-1012174|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=13 June 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2017, Hudlin's film, ''[[Marshall (film)|Marshall]]'', about [[Thurgood Marshall]], the first African-American Supreme Court justice, starring [[Chadwick Boseman]], was released.<ref name=FKBOnline-Boomerang25-2017 /> The screenplay was penned by Michael Koskoff and Jacob Koskoff, and co-stars [[Josh Gad]]. The film was made in [[Buffalo, New York|Buffalo]], [[New York (state)|New York]].<ref name=Deadline-Marshall-OpenRoad-2016>{{cite news|last1=Hipes|first1=Patrick|title=Open Road Acquires Thurgood Marshall Biopic Starring Chadwick Boseman|url=http://deadline.com/2016/06/marshall-movie-chadwick-boseman-open-road-1201769820/|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=9 June 2016}}</ref>\n\nHudlin contributed a story to the ''[[Black Panther (comics)|Black Panther]] Annual'' #1, released in February 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.avclub.com/iconic-creators-return-to-wakanda-in-this-black-panther-1823047658|title=Iconic creators return to Wakanda in this ''Black Panther Annual'' exclusive|last=Sava|first=Oliver|date= February 15, 2018|work=The A.V. Club|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180613015133/https://www.avclub.com/iconic-creators-return-to-wakanda-in-this-black-panther-1823047658 |archivedate= June 13, 2018|url-status= live|df= mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2019, it was announced that Hudlin was directing an upcoming film produced by [[Walt Disney Pictures]], titled ''[[Safety (upcoming film)|Safety]]'', which would be released on [[Disney+]].\n\n== Personal life ==\nIn 2002, Hudlin married Chrisette Hudlin (n\u00e9e Suter), a public relations consultant, in [[Montego Bay, Jamaica|Montego Bay]], [[Jamaica]].<ref name=Variety-Marriage-2003>{{cite news|last1=Variety Staff|title=Chrisette Suter and Reginald Hudlin|url=https://variety.com/2003/scene/people-news/chrisette-suter-and-reginald-hudlin-1117878266/|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=6 January 2003}}</ref><ref name=Essence-KamalaHarris-2016>{{cite news|last1=Owens|first1=Donna M.|title=California Attorney General Kamala Harris Plans to be America's Next Black Female Senator|url=http://www.essence.com/2016/01/13/california-attorney-general-kamala-harris-americas-next-black-female-senator|work=[[Essence (magazine)|Essence]]|date=13 January 2016}}</ref> They have two children.<ref name=HudlinEnt-Top10Heroes-2016>{{cite web|last1=Hudlin|first1=Reginald|title=Top Ten Heroes of the Year|url=http://hudlinentertainment.com/top-ten-heroes-of-the-year/|website=HudlinEntertainment.com|language=en|date=2016}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n;Films\n* 1983: ''House Party'' (Short) \u2013 Director, Writer\n* 1985: ''Reggie's World of Soul'' (Short) \u2013 Director<ref name=BlackDirectorsInHollywood-2003 />{{rp|234}}\n* 1986: ''The Kold Waves'' (Short) \u2013 Director<ref name=BlackDirectorsInHollywood-2003 />{{rp|234}}\n* 1986: ''[[She's Gotta Have It]]'' \u2013 Actor as Dog 4\n* 1990: ''[[House Party (film)|House Party]]'' \u2013 Director, Writer, Actor as Burglar #1\n* 1992: ''[[Boomerang (1992 film)|Boomerang]]'' \u2013 Director, Actor as Street Hustler\n* 1992: ''[[B\u00e9b\u00e9's Kids]]'' (Animated) \u2013 Executive Producer, Writer, Soundtrack: 3 songs: \"I Ain't Havin' It\", \"Freedom Song\", \"Straight Jackin'\"\n* 1993: ''[[Posse (1993 film)|Posse]]'' \u2013 Actor as Reporter 31\n* 1996: ''[[Joe's Apartment]]'' \u2013 Actor as Rodney Roach (voice)\n* 1996: ''[[The Great White Hype]]'' \u2013 Director\n* 1998: ''[[Ride (1998 film)|Ride]]'' \u2013 Producer\n* 2000: ''[[The Ladies Man (2000 film)|The Ladies Man]]'' \u2013 Director, Actor as Aloysius\n* 2002: ''[[Serving Sara]]'' \u2013 Director\n* 2012: ''[[Django Unchained]]'' \u2013 Producer\n* 2017: ''[[Burning Sands (2017 film)|Burning Sands]]'' \u2013 Producer\n* 2017: ''[[Blazing Samurai]]'' (Animated) \u2013 Executive Producer\n* 2017: ''[[Marshall (film)|Marshall]]'' \u2013 Producer, Director\n* 2019: ''[[The Black Godfather (2019 film)|The Black Godfather]]'' \u2013 Director\n* TBA: ''[[Shadowman (comics)#Film|Shadowman]]'' \u2013 Director<ref name=HReporter-Shadowman-2017 />\n;TV movies\n* 1994: ''Cosmic Slop'' \u2013 Executive Producer, Director (segment: \"Space Traders\")\n;TV specials\n* 1994: ''The Last Days of Russell'' \u2013 Co-Executive Producer, Director, Writer\n* 2005: ''[[Richard Pryor: The Funniest Man Dead or Alive]]'' (TV documentary) \u2013 Executive Producer, Director\n* 2006: ''Bring That Year Back 2006: Laugh Now, Cry Later'' \u2013 Network Executive Producer\n* 2006: ''[[BET Hip Hop Awards]]'' \u2013 Executive in Charge of Production\n* 2008: ''[[The BET Honors]]'' \u2013 Executive in Charge of Production\n* 2010: ''Burr and Hart'' \u2013 Director\n* 2013: ''[[44th NAACP Image Awards]]'' \u2013 Executive Producer\n* 2014: ''[[Governors Awards]]'' \u2013 Executive Producer\n* 2014: ''[[45th NAACP Image Awards]]'' \u2013 Executive Producer\n* 2015: ''[[46th NAACP Image Awards]]'' \u2013 Executive Producer\n* 2016: ''[[47th NAACP Image Awards]]'' \u2013 Executive Producer\n* 2016: ''[[88th Academy Awards]]'' \u2013 Producer\n* 2016: ''[[Showtime at the Apollo]]'' \u2013 Executive Producer\n* 2017: ''[[48th NAACP Image Awards]]'' \u2013 Executive Producer\n; TV series\n* 2000: ''[[City of Angels (2000 TV series)|City of Angels]]'' \u2013 Director (1 episode)\n* 2002-2005: ''[[The Bernie Mac Show]]'' \u2013 Producer (7 episodes), Director (11 episodes)\n* 2005: ''[[Everybody Hates Chris]]'' \u2013 Director (1 episode)\n* 2005-2008: ''[[The Boondocks (TV series)|The Boondocks]]'' \u2013 Executive Producer (31 episodes)\n* 2006: ''Somebodies'' \u2013 Executive in Charge of Co-Productions\n* 2007: ''Wifey'' \u2013 Director\n* 2008: ''[[Brothers to Brutha]]'' \u2013 Network Executive\n* 2008-2013: ''BET's Comicview'' \u2013 President of Entertainment (21 episodes)\n* 2009: ''[[Raising the Bar (2008 TV series)|Raising the Bar]]'' \u2013 Director (1 episode)\n* 2009: ''[[The Office (U.S. TV series)|The Office]]'' \u2013 Director (1 episode)\n* 2009: ''[[The Middle (TV series)|The Middle]]'' \u2013 Director (1 episode)\n* 2009-2010: ''[[Modern Family (TV series)|Modern Family]]'' \u2013 Director (2 episodes)\n* 2010: ''[[Better Off Ted]]'' \u2013 Director (1 episode)\n* 2010: ''[[Sons of Tucson]]'' \u2013 Director (1 episode)\n* 2010: ''[[Black Panther (TV series)|Marvel's Black Panther]]'' \u2013 Executive Producer (1 episode), Writer (1 episode), Actor as President (voice) in Episode #1.6\n* 2010-2011: ''[[Outsourced (TV series)|Outsourced]]'' \u2013 Director (2 episodes\n* 2010-2012: ''[[Psych]]'' \u2013 Director (2 episodes)\n* 2011: ''[[Friends with Benefits (TV series)|Friends with Benefits]]'' \u2013 Director (1 episode)\n* 2012: ''[[Are We There Yet? (TV series)|Are We There Yet?]]'' \u2013 Director (3 episodes)\n* 2013: ''[[Bones (TV series)|Bones]]'' \u2013 Director (1 episode)\n* 2013: ''[[How to Live with Your Parents (For the Rest of Your Life)]]'' \u2013 Director (1 episode)\n* 2013: ''[[House Party: Tonight's the Night]]'' \u2013 Writer, based on characters created by (1 episode)\n* 2014-2015: ''[[Bad Judge]]'' \u2013 Director (2 episodes)\n* 2014-2015: ''[[Marry Me (U.S. TV series)|Marry Me]]'' \u2013 Director (2 episodes)\n* 2014-2015: ''[[Murder in the First (TV series)|Murder in the First]]'' \u2013 Director (3 episodes)\n* 2015: ''[[Weird Loners]]'' \u2013 Director (1 episode)\n* 2015: ''[[New Girl]]'' \u2013 Director (1 episode)\n* 2015: ''[[Telenovela (TV series)|Telenovela]]'' \u2013 Director (1 episode)\n* 2016: ''[[Heartbeat (2016 TV series)|Heartbeat]]'' \u2013 Director (1 episode)\n* 2016: ''[[Angel from Hell]]'' \u2013 Director (1 episode)\n* 2016: ''[[Uncle Buck (2016 TV series)|Uncle Buck]]'' \u2013 Director (2 episodes)\n* 2017: ''Blue & Green'' \u2013 Executive Producer \n* 2019: ''[[Black Monday (TV series)|Black Monday]]'' - Director (2 episodes)\n* 2019: ''[[The Last O.G.]]'' - Director (3 episodes)\n\n== Awards ==\n* 1986: Black American Cinema Society (film archives of the Western States Black Research Center), Black Independent Video and Film-maker's Awards, $1,500 first prize for ''House Party'' (short)<ref name=LATimes-BACS-Award-HouseParty-1986 />\n* 1990: [[Sundance Film Festival]], Filmmakers Trophy for ''[[House Party (film)|House Party]]''\n* 1990: [[Sundance Film Festival]], Grand Jury Prize for ''[[House Party (film)|House Party]]'' \u2013 nominee\n* 1990: [[Deauville Film Festival]], Critics Award for ''[[House Party (film)|House Party]]'' \u2013 nominee\n* 1991: [[Film Independent Spirit Award]], Best First Feature for ''[[House Party (film)|House Party]]'' \u2013 nominee\n* 1991: [[Film Independent Spirit Award]], Best Director for ''[[House Party (film)|House Party]]'' \u2013 nominee\n* 1995: [[CableACE]], Dramatic or Theatrical Special for ''Cosmic Slop''\n* 2012: [[American Film Institute Awards 2012]] for ''[[Django Unchained]]'', Top 