 the U.S.}}\n[[File:US bachelor's degree by county in the United States.png|thumb|450px|right|2008\u20132012 bachelor's degree or higher (5-year estimate) by county (percent)]]\n[[File:2012 People 25 Years and Over Who Have Completed an Advanced Degree by State (percent).png|thumb|right|450px| People 25 years and over that have completed an advanced degree by state (percent, 2012)]]\n'''Higher education in the United States''' is an optional stage of [[formal learning]] following [[secondary education]]. [[Higher education]], is also referred as post-secondary education, third-stage, third-level, or tertiary education. It covers stages 5 to 8 on the International [[ISCED 2011]] scale. It is delivered at 4,360 [[Title IV]] degree-granting institutions, known as [[college]]s or [[university|universities]].<ref name=institutions/> These may be [[public university|public]] or [[private university|private universities]], [[liberal arts college]]s, [[Community colleges in the United States|community college]]s, or [[for-profit colleges]]. US higher education is loosely regulated by several third-party organizations.<ref name=\"Baki\u0107-Miri\u0107Gaipov2015\">{{cite book|author1=Nata\u0161a Baki\u0107-Miri\u0107|author2=Davronzhon Erkinovich Gaipov|title=Current Trends and Issues in Higher Education: An International Dialogue|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AZ3zBgAAQBAJ&pg=PA154|date=February 27, 2015|publisher=Cambridge Scholars Publishing|isbn=978-1-4438-7564-6|pages=154\u2013}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the [[National Center for Education Statistics]] (NCES) and [[National Student Clearinghouse]], college enrollment has declined since a peak in 2010\u20132011 and is projected to continue declining or be stagnant for the next two decades.<!--<ref name=\"insidehighered.com1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/admissions/article/2018/01/08/new-book-argues-most-colleges-are-about-face-significant-decline|title=New book argues most colleges are about to face significant decline in prospective students - Inside Higher Ed|website=www.insidehighered.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2018/05/25/614315950/why-is-undergraduate-college-enrollment-declining|title=Why Is Undergraduate College Enrollment Declining?|website=NPR.org}}</ref><ref name=\"nces.ed.gov\">{{cite web |url=https://nces.ed.gov/pubs2018/2018144.pdf |title=The Condition of Education |date=May 2018 |website=National Center for Education Studies |access-date=April 2, 2019 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/quicktakes/2018/05/31/intensive-english-enrollments-us-drop-20|title=Intensive English Enrollments in U.S. Drop 20% - Inside Higher Ed|website=www.insidehighered.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://studentclearinghouse.org/nscblog/fall-2018-overall-postsecondary-enrollments-decreased-1-7-percent-from-last-fall/|title=Fall 2018 Overall Postsecondary Enrollments Decreased 1.7 Percent from Last Fall|first=N. S. C.|last=Blog|date=December 13, 2018|website=studentclearinghouse.org|access-date=March 21, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"ed.gov\">{{cite web |url=https://nces.ed.gov/pubs2019/2019001.pdf |title=Projections of Education Statistics to 2027 |date=February 2019 |website=National Center for Education Studies |access-date=April 2, 2019 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, [[Universitas 21|U21]], a network of research-intensive universities, ranked the US first globally for overall higher education, but only 15th when GDP was factored into the equation. Accounting for GDP, the top 10 nations for higher education in 2018 were Finland, the United Kingdom, Serbia, Denmark, Sweden, Portugal, Switzerland, South Africa, Israel and New Zealand.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://universitas21.com/network/u21-open-resources-and-publications/u21-rankings/u21-ranking-national-higher-education|title=U21 Ranking of National Higher Education Systems 2018 - Universitas 21|author=|date=|website=universitas21.com|access-date=March 21, 2019}}</ref>\n\nStrong research funding helped elite American universities dominate global rankings in the early 21st century, making them attractive to [[international student]]s, professors and researchers.<ref>{{cite web|title=The World University Rankings: Measure by measure: the US is the best of the best|url=http://www.timeshighereducation.co.uk/world-university-rankings/2010-11/world-ranking/analysis/usa-top-universities|date=September 16, 2010|publisher= TSL Education Ltd|author=Phil Baty|access-date=December 12, 2012}}</ref> Other countries, though, are offering incentives to compete for researchers<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2017/07/26/several-countries-launch-campaigns-recruit-research-talent-us-and-elsewhere|title=Several countries launch campaigns to recruit research talent from U.S. and elsewhere|website=Insidehighered.com|access-date=October 18, 2017}}</ref> as funding is threatened in the US <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/quicktakes/2017/07/26/senate-appropriations-bill-cuts-nsf-funding|title=Senate Appropriations Bill Cuts NSF Funding |publisher= Inside Higher Ed|website=Insidehighered.com|access-date=October 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/views/2017/07/21/proposal-indirect-costs-would-put-research-universities-impossible-situation-essay|title=Proposal on indirect costs would put research universities in an impossible situation (essay) |publisher= Inside Higher Ed|website=Insidehighered.com|access-date=October 18, 2017}}</ref> and US dominance of international tables has lessened.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/oxford-cambridge-top-global-rankings-1537966860|title=Oxford, Cambridge Top Global University Rankings: Long-dominant U.S. schools facing stiffer competition from overseas|work=[[Wall Street Journal]]|date=September 26, 2018|author=Erica Snow}}</ref>\n\nThe system has also been blighted by fly-by-night schools, diploma mills, visa mills, and predatory [[for-profit colleges]].<ref name=\"TCTShiremanForProfit\"/><ref name=\"Whitman\"/><ref name=\"Slate19thCent\"/><ref name=\"Robbins\"/> There have been some attempts to reform the system through federal policy such as [[gainful employment]] regulations, but they have been met by resistance.<ref name=\"auto7\"/>\n\nAccording to [[Pew Research Center]] and [[Gallup poll]] surveys, public opinion about colleges has been declining, especially among [[Republican Party (United States)|Republicans]] and the white [[working class in the United States|working class]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.chronicle.com/article/Most-Republicans-Think/240587|title=Most Republicans Think Colleges Are Bad for the Country. Why?|first=Clara|last=Turnage|date=July 10, 2017|newspaper=The Chronicle of Higher Education}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/opinion/op-ed/la-oe-deboer-higher-ed-republican-20170724-story.html|title=Republicans don't trust higher ed. That's a problem for liberal academics|date=July 24, 2017|website=Latimes.com|access-date=October 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.chronicle.com/article/Why-Most-Republicans-Don-t/240691|title=Why Most Republicans Don't Like Higher Education|first=Terry W.|last=Hartle|date=July 19, 2017|newspaper=The Chronicle of Higher Education}}</ref><ref name=\"insidehighered.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2017/08/17/new-data-explain-republican-loss-confidence-higher-education|title=New data explain Republican loss of confidence in higher education|website=Insidehighered.com|access-date=October 18, 2017}}</ref> The higher education industry has been criticized for being unnecessarily expensive, providing a difficult-to-measure service which is seen as vital but in which providers are paid for inputs instead of outputs, which is beset with federal regulations that drive up costs, and payments coming from third parties, not users.<ref name=twsWashPost435>Mitch Daniels, February 6, 2018, Washington Post, [https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/health-care-isnt-our-only-ludicrously-expensive-industry/2018/02/06/6ce64d28-0629-11e8-b48c-b07fea957bd5_story.html Health care isn\u2019t our only ludicrously expensive industry], Retrieved February 7, 2018, \"... by evading accountability for quality, regulating it heavily, and opening a hydrant of public subsidies in the form of government grants and loans, we have constructed another system of guaranteed overruns ... pricing categories that have outpaced health care over recent decades are college tuition, room and board, and books....\"</ref> In a 2018 Pew survey, 61 percent of those polled said that US higher education was headed in the wrong direction.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2018/07/27/survey-most-americans-think-higher-ed-headed-wrong-direction|title=Survey: Most Americans think higher ed is headed in wrong direction|website=www.insidehighered.com}}</ref> A 2019 Gallup survey found that, among graduates who strongly felt a purpose in life was important, \"only 40 percent said they had found a meaningful career after college.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2019/04/11/gallup-bates-report-shows-graduates-want-sense-purpose-careers|title=Gallup, Bates report shows graduates want a sense of purpose in careers|author=|date=|website=www.insidehighered.com|access-date=April 17, 2019}}</ref>\n-->\nThe US is unique in its investment in highly competitive [[NCAA]] sports, particularly in [[American football]] and [[basketball]], with large sports stadiums and arenas.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/richardvedder/2018/03/14/perpetual-madness-not-just-in-march/|title=The Three Reasons College Sports Is An Ugly Business|first=Richard|last=Vedder|website=Forbes}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n{{main|History of higher education in the United States}}\n\n===Colonial era to 19th century===\n[[File:Rear view of the Wren Building, College of William & Mary in Williamsburg, Virginia, USA (2008-04-23).jpg|thumb|right|The [[Wren Building]] at the [[College of William & Mary]] is the oldest academic building in the United States, dating back to 1695.]]\n[[File:1904 World's Fair Administration Building (Brookings Hall, Washington University) seen from the southeast with the Italian Pavilion in the foreground.jpg|thumb|[[Brookings Hall]] of [[Washington University in St. Louis]], established in 1853]]\nReligious denominations established early colleges in order to train ministers. [[Harvard University|Harvard College]] was founded by the colonial legislature in 1636. According to historian John Thelin, most instructors were lowly paid 'tutors'.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Thelin |first1=John R. |title=A History of American Higher Education |date=April 2, 2019 |publisher=Johns Hopkins University Press |isbn=978-1421428833 |page=17 |edition=3rd}}</ref> In Ebony and Ivy, Craig Steven Wilder documented the history of early higher education in the US, including the oppression of indigenous people and enslaved Africans at elite colleges.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Wilder |first1=Craig David |title=Ebony and Ivy |date=September 2, 2014 |publisher=Bloomsbury |isbn=9781608194025 |edition=1st}}</ref>\n\nProtestants and Catholics opened over hundreds of small denominational colleges in the 19th century.  In 1899 they enrolled 46 percent of all U.S. undergraduates. Many closed or merged but in 1905 there were over 500 in operation.<ref>David B. Potts, \"American colleges in the nineteenth century: From localism to denominationalism.\" ''History of Education Quarterly'' (1971): 363\u2013380, data on pp. 373, 374. [https://www.jstor.org/stable/367036 in JSTOR].</ref><ref>David B. Potts, ''Baptist colleges in the development of American society, 1812\u20131861'' (1988).</ref> Catholics opened several women's colleges in the early 20th century. Schools were small, with a limited undergraduate curriculum based on the liberal arts. Students were drilled in Greek, Latin, geometry, ancient history, logic, ethics and rhetoric, with few discussions and no lab sessions. Originality and creativity were not prized, but exact repetition was rewarded. College presidents typically enforced strict discipline, and upperclassman enjoyed hazing freshman. Many students were younger than 17, and most colleges also operated a preparatory school. There were no organized sports, or Greek-letter fraternities, but literary societies were active. Tuition was low and scholarships were few. Many of their students were sons of clergymen; most planned professional careers as ministers, lawyers or teachers.<ref>Frederick Rudolph, ''The American College and University: A History'' (1991) pp. 3\u201322</ref>\n\nThe nation's small colleges helped young men make the transition from rural farms to complex urban occupations. These schools promoted upward mobility by preparing ministers and providing towns with a core of community leaders. Elite colleges became increasingly exclusive and contributed little upward social mobility. By concentrating on the offspring of wealthy families, and ministers, elite Eastern colleges such as Harvard, played a role in the formation of a Northeastern elite.<ref>Michael Katz, \"The Role of American Colleges in the Nineteenth Century\", ''History of Education Quarterly'', Vol. 23, No. 2 (Summer, 1983), pp. 215\u2013223 [https://www.jstor.org/stable/368160 in JSTOR], summarizing Colin B. Burke, ''American Collegiate Populations: A Test of the Traditional View'' (New York University Press, 1982) and Peter Dobkin Hall, ''The Organization of American Culture: Private Institutions, Elites, and the Origins of American Nationality'' (New York University Press, 1982)</ref>\n\n====Catholic colleges and universities====\n{{main|History of Catholic education in the United States#Colleges and universities}}\n[[File:Main Building at the University of Notre Dame.jpg|thumb|The Main Building at the [[University of Notre Dame]], the best known Catholic university in the United States]]\nThe [[Association of Catholic Colleges and Universities]] was founded in 1899 and continues to facilitate the exchange of information and methods.<ref>{{cite book|author=LaBelle, Jeffrey|title=Catholic Colleges in the 21st Century: A Road Map for Campus Ministry|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=x-n-P2hNtFQC&pg=PT32|year=2011|publisher=Paulist Press|isbn=978-1893757899}}</ref> Vigorous debate in recent decades has focused on how to balance Catholic and academic roles, with conservatives arguing that bishops should exert more control to guarantee orthodoxy.<ref>John Rodden, \"Less 'Catholic,' More 'catholic'? American Catholic Universities Since Vatican II.\" ''Society'' (2013) 50#1 pp. 21\u201327.</ref><ref>S.J. Currie, and L. Charles. \"Pursuing Jesuit, Catholic identity and mission at US Jesuit colleges and universities.\" ''Catholic Education: A Journal of Inquiry and Practice'' (2011) 14#3 pp. 4ff [http://digitalcommons.lmu.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1683&context=ce online]</ref><ref>Matthew Thomas Larsen, ''The Duty and Right of the Diocesan Bishop to Watch Over the Preservation and Strengthening of the Catholic Character of Catholic Universities in His Diocese\" (PhD dissertation Catholic University of America, 2012)</ref>\n\n===Timeline of key federal legislation===\n* [[Morrill Act]] (1862 and 1890)\n* [[Smith\u2013Hughes Act]] or National Vocational Education Act (1917)<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Hillison |first1=John |title=The Coaltion that Supported the Smith-Hughes Act or a Case for Strange Bedfellows |journal=Journal of Career and Technical Education |date=1995 |volume= 11 |issue=2 |pages=4\u201311 |url=https://files.eric.ed.gov/fulltext/EJ504569.pdf |accessdate=22 June 2019|doi=10.21061/jcte.v11i2.582 }}</ref>\n* [[G.I. Bill]] (1944)\n* [[National Defense Education Act]] (1958)\n* [[Higher Education Act of 1965|Higher Education Act]] (1965)\n* [[Education Amendments of 1972|Education Amendments]] (1972)\n\n===20th century===\nAt the beginning of the 20th century, less than 1,000 colleges with 160,000 students existed in the US. The number of colleges skyrocketed in waves, during the early and mid 20th century. State universities grew from small institutions of fewer than 1000 students to campuses with 40,000 more students, with networks of regional campuses around the state. In turn, regional campuses broke away and became separate universities. {{citation needed|date=June 2019}}\n\nTo handle the explosive growth of K\u201312 education, every state set up a network of teachers' colleges, beginning with Massachusetts in the 1830s. After 1950, they became state colleges and then state universities with a broad curriculum.{{citation needed|date=June 2019}}\n\nMajor new trends included the development of the [[Junior college#United States|junior colleges]]. They were usually set up by City school systems starting in the 1920s.<ref>Leonard V. Koos, ''The Junior College Movement'' (1924).</ref> By the 1960s they were renamed as \"community colleges.\"\n\nJunior colleges grew from 20 in number In 1909, to 170 in 1919. By 1922, 37 states had set up 70 junior colleges, enrolling about 150 students each. Meanwhile, another 137 were privately operated, with about 60 students each. Rapid expansion continued in the 1920s, with 440 junior colleges in 1930 enrolling about 70,000 students. The peak year for private institutions came in 1949, when there were 322 junior colleges in all; 180 were affiliated with churches, 108 were independent non-profit, and 34 were private Schools run for-profit.<ref>Cohen and Brawer, ''The American Community College'' (4th ed. 2003) pp. 13\u201314</ref>\n\nMany factors contributed to rapid growth of community colleges. Students parents and businessmen wanted nearby, low-cost schools to provide training for the growing white-collar labor force, as well as for more advanced technical jobs in the blue collar sphere. Four-year colleges were also growing, albeit not as fast; however, many of them were located in rural or small-town areas away from the fast-growing metropolis. Community colleges continue as open-enrollment, low-cost institutions with a strong component of vocational education, as well as a low-cost preparation for transfer students into four-year schools. They appeal to a poorer, older, less prepared element.<ref>Jesse P. Bogue, ed. ''American Junior Colleges'' (American council on education, 1948)</ref><ref>Cohen and Brawer, ''The American Community College'' (6th ed. 2013)</ref>\n\nCollege students were involved in [[social movements]] long before the 20th century, but the most dramatic student movements rose in the 1960s. In the 1960s, students organized for [[civil rights]] and against the [[Vietnam War]]. In the 1970s, students led movements for [[women's rights]] and [[gay rights]], as well as protests against South African [[apartheid]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.freshu.io/taylor-lang/the-biggest-social-movements-led-by-college-students-in-history|title=11 Past and Present Social Movements Led By College Students|website=Freshu.io|access-date=October 18, 2017}}</ref>\n\nWhile for-profit colleges originated during Colonial times, growth in these schools was most apparent from the 1980s to about 2011. For-profit college enrollment, however, has declined significantly since 2011, after several federal investigations. For-profit colleges were criticized for predatory marketing and sales practices.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Q8qnCwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q=diploma+mills+book|title=Diploma Mills: How For-Profit Colleges Stiffed Students, Taxpayers, and the American Dream|first=A. J.|last=Angulo|date=January 27, 2016|publisher=JHU Press|via=Google Books|isbn=9781421420073}}</ref> The failures of [[Corinthian Colleges]] and [[ITT Technical Institute]] were the most remarkable closings.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/itt-technical-institute-to-close-after-government-cuts-off-new-funding-1473163181|title=ITT Technical Institute Shuts Down After Government Cut Off New Funding|first=Melissa|last=Korn|date=September 7, 2016|website=Wsj.com|access-date=October 18, 2017}}</ref> In 2018, the documentary ''Fail State'' chronicled the boom and bust of for-profit colleges, highlighting the abuses that led to their downfall.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.texasobserver.org/fail-state-delves-shadowy-world-profit-colleges/|title='Fail State' Delves into the Shadowy World of For-Profit Colleges|date=October 27, 2017|website=The Texas Observer}}</ref>\n\n===21st century===\nChanging technology, mergers and closings, and politics have resulted in dramatic changes in US higher education during the 21st century.\n\n====Online education and MOOCs====\nOnline education has grown in the early 21st century. More than 6.3 million students in the U.S. took at least one online course in fall 2016.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://www.usnews.com/higher-education/online-education/articles/2018-01-11/study-more-students-are-enrolling-in-online-courses |title=Study: More Students Are Enrolling in Online Courses |magazine=US News & World Report |date=January 11, 2018 |first=Jordan |last=Friedman |access-date=April 2, 2019 }}</ref> While online attendance has increased, confidence among chief academic officers has decreased from 70.8 percent in 2015 to 63.3 percent in 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://onlinelearningconsortium.org/news_item/report-one-four-students-enrolled-online-courses/|title=Report: One in Four Students Enrolled in Online Courses|author=|date=|website=OLC|access-date=January 21, 2019}}</ref> In 2017, about 15% of all students attended exclusively [[online]], and competition for online students has been increasing<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2017/05/22/reports-finds-rising-competition-online-education-market|title=Reports finds rising competition in online education market|website=Insidehighered.com|access-date=October 18, 2017}}</ref>\n\nBy 2018, more than one hundred short-term [[coding bootcamp]]s existed in the US. Programs were available at Harvard University's extension school and the extension schools at Georgia Tech, University of Pennsylvania, Cal Berkeley, Northwestern, UCLA, University of North Carolina, University of Texas, George Washington, Vanderbilt University, and Rutgers through Trilogy Education Services.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/quicktakes/2018/12/07/harvard-offers-first-coding-boot-camp|title=Harvard Offers First Coding Boot Camp - Inside Higher Ed|website=www.insidehighered.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.trilogyed.com/universities/|title=Universities|website=Trilogy Education Services}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, researchers at George Mason University concluded that online education has \"contributed to increasing gaps in educational success across socioeconomic groups while failing to improve affordability\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/digital-learning/article/2019/01/16/online-learning-fails-deliver-finds-report-aimed-discouraging|title=Online learning fails to deliver, finds report aimed at discouraging politicians from deregulating - Inside Higher Ed|author=|date=|website=www.insidehighered.com|access-date=January 21, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://mason.gmu.edu/~sprotops/OnlineEd.pdf |title=Does Online Education Live Up to Its Promise? A Look at the Evidence and Implications for Federal Policy |date=January 2019 |first1=Spiros |last1=Protopsaltis |first2=Sandy |last2=Baum }}{{self-published inline|date=May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Hill |first1=Phil |date=January 27, 2019 |title=Deeply Flawed GMU Report on Online Education Asks Good Questions But Provides Misguided Analysis |url=https://mfeldstein.com/deeply-flawed-gmu-report-on-online-education/ |website=e-Literate }}</ref>\n\nA MOOC is a ''[[massive open online course]]'' aimed at unlimited participation and open access via the web. It became popular in 2010\u201314. In addition to traditional course materials such as filmed lectures, readings, and [[problem set]]s, many MOOCs provide interactive user forums to support community interactions between students, professors, and teaching assistants.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Bozkurt |first1=Aras |last2=Akgun-Ozbek |first2=Ela |last3=Yilmazel |first3=Sibel |last4=Erdogdu |first4=Erdem |last5=Ucar |first5=Hasan |last6=Guler |first6=Emel |last7=Sezgin |first7=Sezan |last8=Karadeniz |first8=Abdulkadir |last9=Sen-Ersoy |first9=Nazife |last10=Goksel-Canbek |first10=Nil |last11=Dincer |first11=Gokhan Deniz |last12=Ari |first12=Suleyman |last13=Aydin |first13=Cengiz Hakan |title=Trends in distance education research: A content analysis of journals 2009-2013 |journal=The International Review of Research in Open and Distributed Learning |date=20 January 2015 |volume=16 |issue=1 |doi=10.19173/irrodl.v16i1.1953 }}</ref> [[Robert Zemsky]] (2014), of the [[University of Pennsylvania Graduate School of Education]] notes that they at first seemed to be an extremely inexpensive method of bringing top teachers at low cost directly to students. However, very few students\u2014usually under 5%\u2014were able to finish a MOOC course. He argues that they have passed their peak: \"They came; they conquered very little; and now they face substantially diminished prospects.\"<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Zemsky | first1 = Robert | year = 2014 | title = With a MOOC MOOC here and a MOOC MOOC there, here a MOOC, there a MOOC, everywhere a MOOC MOOC | jstor = 10.5325/jgeneeduc.63.4.0237 | journal = Journal of General Education | volume = 63 | issue = 4| pages = 237\u2013243 | doi=10.1353/jge.2014.0029}}</ref> In 2019, researchers at MIT found that MOOCs had completion rates of 3 percent and that the number of people taking these courses has been declining since 2012\u201313.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/digital-learning/article/2019/01/16/study-offers-data-show-moocs-didnt-achieve-their-goals|title=Study offers data to show MOOCs didn't achieve their goals - Inside Higher Ed|author=|date=|website=www.insidehighered.com|access-date=January 21, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOnline programs for many universities are often managed by privately owned companies called OPMs. The OPMs include [[2U (company)|2U]], [[HotChalk]] and iDesign.\nTrace Urdan, managing director at Tyton Partners, \"estimates that the market for OPMs and related services will be worth nearly $8 billion by 2020.\"\n<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.huffpost.com/highline/article/capitalist-takeover-college/ |title=The Creeping Capitalist Takeover of Higher Education |newspaper=Huffpost |date=April 1, 2019 |first=Kevin |last=Carey |access-date=April 2, 2019 }}</ref>\n\n====Financial difficulties, mergers and downsizing====\nHundreds of colleges are expected to close or merge, according to research from [[Ernst & Young]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chronicle.com/article/Networked-U-s-This-Is-What/241724|title=Networked U.'s: This Is What Will Save Higher Ed|date=November 8, 2017}}</ref> The US Department of Education publishes a monthly list of campus and learning site closings. Typically there are 300 to 1000 closings per year.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www2.ed.gov/offices/OSFAP/PEPS/closedschools.html|title=PEPS Closed School Monthly Reports|author=|date=|website=www2.ed.gov|access-date=January 21, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |url=https://search.proquest.com/openview/186c697cf1f762decb958cbf24ce392b/1?pq-origsite=gscholar&cbl=47536 |title=An Analysis of Closed Colleges and Universities |journal=Planning for Higher Education Journal |volume=44 |number=4 |date=July 2016 |first1=Kristin |last1=Stowe |first2=David |last2=Komasara |access-date=April 2, 2019 |via=ProQuest |url-access=limited }}</ref> \nNotable college closings include for-profit [[Corinthian Colleges]] (2015), [[ITT Technical Institute]] (2016), [[Brightwood College]] and [[Virginia College]](2018).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://diverseeducation.com/article/92884/|title=Court Rules Against Accrediting Agency of ITT Tech, Corinthian Colleges|last=cmaadmin|date=February 21, 2017|website=diverseeducation.com|access-date=January 27, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/education/2018/12/06/virginia-college-brightwood-college-closing-for-profit-operator-cites-dwindling-enrollment/ |title=Virginia College and Brightwood College closing; for-profit operator cites dwindling enrollment |newspaper=The Washington Post |date=December 6, 2018 |first=Danielle |last=Douglas-Gabriel |access-date=April 2, 2019 }}</ref> Private college closings include [[Wheelock College]] (2018) and [[Green Mountain College]] (2019).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2019/01/25/green-mountain-college-tried-numerous-strategies-still-closing|title=Green Mountain College tried numerous strategies but is still closing|author=|date=|website=www.insidehighered.com|access-date=January 27, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2017, [[Moody's]] credit rating agency downgraded the US higher education outlook from stable to negative, \"citing financial strains at both public and private four-year institutions.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.chronicle.com/article/Moody-s-Downgrades-Higher/241983|title=Moody's Downgrades Higher Ed's Outlook From 'Stable' to 'Negative'|first=Adam|last=Harris|date=December 5, 2017|access-date=January 27, 2019|via=The Chronicle of Higher Education}}</ref> In June 2018, Moody's released data on declining college enrollments and constraints, noting that tuition pricing would suppress tuition revenue growth.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/quicktakes/2018/06/01/moodys-declining-enrollment-squeezing-tuition-revenue|title=Moody's: Declining Enrollment Is Squeezing Tuition Revenue - Inside Higher Ed|author=|date=|website=www.insidehighered.com|access-date=January 27, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOther businesses related to higher education have also had financial difficulties. In May 2019, two academic publishers, [[Cengage]] and [[McGraw Hill]], merged.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/mcgraw-hill-cengage-plan-all-stock-merger-11556683590|title=McGraw-Hill to Merge With Rival Textbook Publisher|first=Cara|last=Lombardo|date=May 1, 2019|via=www.wsj.com}}</ref>\n\n====Protests and political clashes====\n[[Student protests]] and clashes between left and right appeared on several US campuses in 2017.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/08/04/education/edlife/antifa-collective-university-california-berkeley.html|title=Behind Berkeley's Semester of Hate|website=Nytimes.com|access-date=October 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2017/08/14/white-supremacy-turning-campus-speeches-and-leaflets|title=White supremacy is turning up on campus in speeches and leaflets|website=Insidehighered.com|access-date=October 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/08/04/education/edlife/protests-claremont-college-student-demands.html|title=More Diversity Means More Demands|website=Nytimes.com|access-date=October 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/colleges-brace-for-more-violence-charlottesville-rally-white-supremacist-demonstrators/|title=Colleges brace for more violence in wake of Charlottesville rally|website=Cbsnews.com|access-date=October 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2017/08/15/college-students-unmasked-unite-right-protesters|title=College students unmasked as 'Unite the Right' protesters|website=Insidehighered.com|access-date=October 18, 2017}}</ref> On August 11, 2017, [[white nationalists]] and members of the [[alt-right]] rallied at the [[University of Virginia]], protesting the removal of a statue of [[Robert E. Lee]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.chronicle.com/article/UVa-Employee-Suffers-a-Stroke/240942|title=UVa Employee Suffers a Stroke After Campus Clash With White Supremacists|first1=Jack|last1=Stripling|first2=Nell|last2=Gluckman|date=August 16, 2017|newspaper=The Chronicle of Higher Education}}</ref> The following day, one person died during protests in Charlottesville.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/08/13/opinion/university-virginia-uva-protests-charlottesville.html|title=Opinion \u2013 What U.Va. Students Saw in Charlottesville|date=August 13, 2017|website=Nytimes.com|access-date=October 18, 2017}}</ref> Following this event, speaking engagements by [[Richard B. Spencer|Richard Spencer]] were canceled at [[Texas A&M University]] and the [[University of Florida]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2017/08/17/public-universities-are-solid-ground-cancel-richard-spencer-events-legal-experts-say|title=Public universities are on solid ground to cancel Richard Spencer events, legal experts say|website=Insidehighered.com|access-date=October 18, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Functions==\nUS higher education functions as an institution of knowledge, but has several secondary functions. According to Marcus Ford, the primary function went through four phases in American history: preserving Christian civilization, advancing the national interest, research, and growing the global economy<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Ford |first1=Marcus |title=The Functions of Higher Education |journal=American Journal of Economics and Sociology |date=May 2017 |volume=76 |issue=3 |pages=559\u2013578 |doi=10.1111/ajes.12187 }}</ref> It has also served as a source for professional credentials, as a vehicle for social mobility, and as a social sorter.<ref>{{Cite journal | url=https://www.chronicle.com/article/The-Dirty-Little-Secret-of/20548 | title=The Dirty Little Secret of Credential Inflation| journal=The Chronicle of Higher Education| date=September 27, 2002}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Collins |first1=Randall |title=Functional and Conflict Theories of Educational Stratification |journal=American Sociological Review |date=December 1971 |volume=36 |issue=6 |pages=1002\u201319 |doi=10.2307/2093761 |jstor=2093761 }}</ref> The college functions as a 'status marker', \"signaling membership in the educated class, and a place to meet spouses of similar status\".<ref>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/george-will-subprime-college-educations/2012/06/08/gJQA4fGiOV_story.html Subprime college educations]</ref>\n\nIn 2018, [[Universitas 21|Universitas 21 (U21)]], the network of research-intensive universities, ranked the US first globally for overall higher education, but only 15th when [[Gross domestic product|GDP]] was factored into the equation. Accounting for GDP, the top 10 nations for higher education in 2018 were Finland, the United Kingdom, Serbia, Denmark, Sweden, Portugal, Switzerland, South Africa, Israel and New Zealand.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://universitas21.com/network/u21-open-resources-and-publications/u21-rankings/u21-ranking-national-higher-education|title=U21 Ranking of National Higher Education Systems 2018 - Universitas 21|author=|date=|website=universitas21.com|access-date=March 21, 2019}}</ref>\n\nStrong research funding helped 'elite American universities' dominate global rankings in the early 21st century, making them attractive to [[international student]]s, professors and researchers.<ref>{{cite web|title=The World University Rankings: Measure by measure: the US is the best of the best|url=http://www.timeshighereducation.co.uk/world-university-rankings/2010-11/world-ranking/analysis/usa-top-universities|date=September 16, 2010|publisher= TSL Education Ltd|author=Phil Baty|access-date=December 12, 2012}}</ref> Other countries, though, are offering incentives to compete for researchers<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2017/07/26/several-countries-launch-campaigns-recruit-research-talent-us-and-elsewhere|title=Several countries launch campaigns to recruit research talent from U.S. and elsewhere|website=Insidehighered.com|access-date=October 18, 2017}}</ref> as funding is threatened in the US<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/quicktakes/2017/07/26/senate-appropriations-bill-cuts-nsf-funding|title=Senate Appropriations Bill Cuts NSF Funding |publisher= Inside Higher Ed|website=Insidehighered.com|access-date=October 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/views/2017/07/21/proposal-indirect-costs-would-put-research-universities-impossible-situation-essay|title=Proposal on indirect costs would put research universities in an impossible situation (essay) |publisher= Inside Higher Ed|website=Insidehighered.com|access-date=October 18, 2017}}</ref> and US dominance of international tables has lessened.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/oxford-cambridge-top-global-rankings-1537966860|title=Oxford, Cambridge Top Global University Rankings: Long-dominant U.S. schools facing stiffer competition from overseas|work=[[Wall Street Journal]]|date=September 26, 2018|author=Erica Snow}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=O\u2019Malley |first1=Brendan |title=US suffers worst global ranking performance in 16 years |url=https://www.universityworldnews.com/post.php?story=20190621130009586 |website=universityworldnews.com |accessdate=24 June 2019}}</ref> The system has also been blighted by fly-by-night schools, diploma mills, visa mills, and predatory [[for-profit colleges]].<ref name=\"Whitman\">{{cite web|url=https://tcf.org/content/report/vietnam-vets-new-student-loan-program-bring-new-college-scams/|title=Vietnam Vets and a New Student Loan Program Bring New College Scams|date=February 13, 2017|author=Davis Whitman|publisher=[[The Century Foundation]]}}</ref><ref name=\"Robbins\">{{cite web|author=Liz Robbins|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/05/06/nyregion/students-at-fake-university-say-they-were-collateral-damage-in-sting-operation.html|work=New York Times|date=May 5, 2016|title=Students at Fake University Say They Were Collateral Damage in Sting Operation}}</ref><ref name=\"TCTShiremanForProfit\">{{cite web|url=https://tcf.org/content/report/policies-work-dont-work-stop-predatory-profit-colleges/|title=The Policies That Work\u2014and Don't Work\u2014to Stop Predatory For-Profit Colleges|author=Robert Shireman|publisher=[[The Century Foundation]]|date=May 20, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Slate19thCent\">{{cite web|url=http://www.slate.com/articles/life/education/2016/07/are_for_profit_colleges_bad_a_j_angulo_explains_the_history_of_for_profit.html|title=19th-Century For-Profit Colleges Spawned Trump University|first=Rebecca|last=Onion|date=July 27, 2016|work=Slate}}</ref> There have been some attempts to reform the system through federal policy such as [[gainful employment]] regulations, particularly through the Department of Education's [[College Scorecard]], which enables students to see the socio-economic diversity, SAT/ACT scores, graduation rates, and average earnings and debt of graduates at all colleges.<ref>{{cite web\n | url =https://cew.georgetown.edu/cew-reports/collegeroi/\n | title =A First Try at ROI: Ranking 4,500 Colleges\n | date =5 November 2019\n | website =Center on Education and the Workforce\n | publisher =Georgetown University\n | access-date =16 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nAccording to [[Pew Research Center]] and [[Gallup poll]] surveys, public opinion about colleges has been declining, especially among [[Republican Party (United States)|Republicans]] and the white [[working class in the United States|working class]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.chronicle.com/article/Most-Republicans-Think/240587|title=Most Republicans Think Colleges Are Bad for the Country. Why?|first=Clara|last=Turnage|date=July 10, 2017|newspaper=The Chronicle of Higher Education}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/opinion/op-ed/la-oe-deboer-higher-ed-republican-20170724-story.html|title=Republicans don't trust higher ed. That's a problem for liberal academics|date=July 24, 2017|website=Latimes.com|access-date=October 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.chronicle.com/article/Why-Most-Republicans-Don-t/240691|title=Why Most Republicans Don't Like Higher Education|first=Terry W.|last=Hartle|date=July 19, 2017|newspaper=The Chronicle of Higher Education}}</ref><ref name=\"insidehighered.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2017/08/17/new-data-explain-republican-loss-confidence-higher-education|title=New data explain Republican loss of confidence in higher education|website=Insidehighered.com|access-date=October 18, 2017}}</ref> The higher education industry has been criticized for being unnecessarily expensive, providing a difficult-to-measure service which is seen as vital but in which providers are paid for inputs instead of outputs, which is beset with federal regulations that drive up costs, and payments coming from third parties, not users.<ref name=twsWashPost435>Mitch Daniels, February 6, 2018, Washington Post, [https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/health-care-isnt-our-only-ludicrously-expensive-industry/2018/02/06/6ce64d28-0629-11e8-b48c-b07fea957bd5_story.html Health care isn\u2019t our only ludicrously expensive industry], Retrieved February 7, 2018, \"... by evading accountability for quality, regulating it heavily, and opening a hydrant of public subsidies in the form of government grants and loans, we have constructed another system of guaranteed overruns ... pricing categories that have outpaced health care over recent decades are college tuition, room and board, and books....\"</ref> In a 2018 Pew survey, 61 percent of those polled said that US higher education was headed in the wrong direction.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2018/07/27/survey-most-americans-think-higher-ed-headed-wrong-direction|title=Survey: Most Americans think higher ed is headed in wrong direction|website=www.insidehighered.com}}</ref> A 2019 Gallup survey found that, among graduates who strongly felt a purpose in life was important, \"only 40 percent said they had found a meaningful career after college.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2019/04/11/gallup-bates-report-shows-graduates-want-sense-purpose-careers|title=Gallup, Bates report shows graduates want a sense of purpose in careers|author=|date=|website=www.insidehighered.com|access-date=April 17, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Types of colleges and universities==\n[[File:Harvard Yard, Dudesleeper.jpg|right|thumb|200px|[[Harvard University]]: [[Harvard Yard]] with freshman dorms in the background]]\n{{See also|List of American institutions of higher education|List of state universities in the United States}}US colleges and universities offer diverse educational venues: some emphasize a [[vocational education|vocational]], [[business]], [[engineering]], or technical curriculum (like [[Institute of Technology (United States)|polytechnic universities]] and [[Land-grant university|land-grant universities]]) and others emphasize a [[liberal arts]] curriculum. Many combine some or all of the above, as comprehensive universities.\n\n===Terminology===\nThe term \"college\" refers to one of three types of education institutions: stand-alone higher level education institutions that are not components of a university.\n# [[community colleges in the United States|community colleges]]\n# [[Liberal arts colleges in the United States|liberal arts colleges]]\n# a college within a university, mostly the undergraduate institution of a university. \n[[File:MIT Dome night1 Edit.jpg|thumb|right|200px|left|The Great Dome of [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]] (MIT), a university adopting the [[polytechnic university model]].]]\n\nAlmost all colleges and universities are [[coeducation]]al. A dramatic transition occurred in the 1970s, when most [[Men's colleges in the United States|men's colleges]] started to accept women. Over 80% of the women's colleges of the 1960s have closed or merged, leaving fewer than 50. Over 100 [[historically black colleges and universities]] (HBCUs) operate, both private and public.\n\nSome [[U.S. states]] offer higher education at two year \"colleges\" formerly called \"[[community college]]s\". The change requires cooperation between community colleges and local universities.\n\n[[File:College degrees graph.png|upright|thumb|right|Share of all bachelor's degrees awarded by field]]\n\nFour-year colleges often provide the [[bachelor's degree]], most commonly the [[Bachelor of Arts]] (B.A.) or [[Bachelor of Science]] (B.S.). They are primarily either [[Undergraduate education|undergraduate only institutions]] (e.g. [[liberal arts college]]s), or the undergraduate institution of a university (such as [[Harvard College]] and [[Yale College]]).\n[[File:DeSeversky.jpg|thumb|right|The DeSeversky Mansion on the [[Old Westbury]] campus of [[New York Institute of Technology]].]]\n\nHigher education has led to the creation of [[Higher education accreditation|accreditation organizations]], independent of the government, to vouch for the quality of degrees. They rate institutions on academic quality, the quality of their libraries, the publishing records of their faculty, the degrees which their faculty hold, and their financial solvency.{{citation needed|date=June 2019}} Accrediting agencies have been criticized for possible conflicts of interest that lead to favorable results.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://economics21.org/sites/e21/files/Cooper.NotImpartialReport.Final_.pdf|title=Not Impartial: Examining Accreditation Commissioners' Conflicts of Interest|website=Economics21.org|access-date=October 18, 2017}}</ref> Non-accredited institutions exist, but the students are not eligible for federal loans.\n\n===Student entry into higher education===\nUnder the American secondary education system, students select compulsory and elective courses while at [[High school (North America)|high school]]. Completing each course to the schools satisfaction gains the student a number of credits. To enter tertiary education the student will be doing a number of [[Advanced placement]] courses that will gain the highest number of credits. A student graduates from High School when the minimum number of credits has been achieved, and will be accepted by a college when their required number is achieved. The college system is similar: each course passed earns a set number of credits, and the student graduates with an undergraduate degree when the set number have been earned. The credits travel with the student should they change institution. {{citation needed|date=June 2019}} <!-- This is a paragraph that is needed for non-US to follow the rest of the article- but it must be corrected by someone in the US-->\n\n===Universities===\n[[File:Alumni Hall 1889 Sun.jpg|thumb|right|[[Saint Anselm College]], a [[New England]] liberal arts college]]\nUniversities are educational institutions with undergraduate and graduate programs. For historical reasons, some universities<ref>e.g., [[Boston College]], [[Dartmouth College]], [[The College of William & Mary]], and [[College of Charleston]]</ref> have retained the term ''college'' instead of \"university\" for their name. [[Graduate school|Graduate programs]] grant a variety of [[master's degree]]s (like the [[Master of Arts]] (M.A.), [[Master of Science]] (M.S.), [[Master of Business Administration]] (M.B.A.) or [[Master of Fine Arts]] (M.F.A.) in addition to [[doctorate]]s such as the [[Doctor of Philosophy|Ph.D]]. The [[Carnegie Classification of Institutions of Higher Education]] distinguishes among institutions on the basis of the prevalence of degrees they grant and considers the granting of [[master's degree]]s necessary, although not sufficient, for an institution to be classified as a university.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.carnegiefoundation.org/classifications/index.asp?key=798|title=Basic Classification Technical Details|publisher=Carnegie Foundation for the Advancement of Teaching|date=n.d.|access-date=March 20, 2007}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Csuofficeofthechancellor.jpg|thumb|right|Public [[California State University]], Office of the Chancellor in [[Long Beach, California|Long Beach]], [[California]]]]\nSome universities have [[Professional degree|professional schools]]. Examples include [[journalism school]], [[business school]], [[medical school]]s, [[pharmacy school]]s ([[Doctor of Pharmacy|Pharm.D.]]), and [[dental school]]s. A common practice is to refer to these disparate faculties within universities as ''colleges'' or ''schools''.{{citation needed|date=June 2019}}\n\nThe American university system is largely [[Decentralization|decentralized]]. [[Public university|Public universities]] are administered by the individual [[U.S. state|states]] and [[Territories of the United States|territories]], usually as part of a [[state university system]]. Except for the [[United States service academies]] and [[staff college]]s, the [[Federal government of the United States|federal government]] does not directly regulate universities. However, it can offer federal grants and any institution that receives federal funds must certify that it has adopted and implemented a drug prevention program that meets federal regulations.<ref>{{cite news|title=Marijuana illegal on campus despite Amendment 64|first=Dezarae|last=Yoder|date=February 25, 2013|work=[[The Scribe (UCCS)|The Scribe]]|url=http://www.uccsscribe.com/news/marijuana-illegal-on-campus-despite-amendment-64-1.2813082}}</ref><ref>{{USCFR|34|86}}; specifically {{USCFR|34|86|100}}</ref>\n\nEach state supports at least one state university and several support several. At one extreme, California has three public higher education systems: the 10-campus [[University of California]], the 23-campus [[California State University]], and the 112-campus [[California Community Colleges System]]. In contrast, [[List of colleges and universities in Wyoming|Wyoming]] supports a single state university.  Public universities often have large student bodies, with introductory classes numbering in the hundreds, with some undergraduate classes taught by graduate students. [[Tribal college]]s operated on [[Indian reservation]]s by some [[federally recognized tribes]] are also public institutions.{{citation needed|date=June 2019}}\n\nMany [[Private university|private universities]] exist. Some are [[Secularity|secular]] and others are involved in [[religious education]]. Some are [[Non-denominational Christianity|non-denominational]], and some are affiliated with a certain sect or church, such as [[Catholic Church in the United States|Roman Catholicism]] (with different institutions often sponsored by particular [[religious institute]]s such as the [[Society of Jesus|Jesuits]]) or religions such as [[Lutheranism]] or [[Mormonism]]. [[Seminary|Seminaries]] are private institutions for those preparing to become members of the [[clergy]]. Most private schools (like all public schools) are [[Non-profit organization|non-profit]], although some are [[For-profit school|for-profit]].{{citation needed|date=June 2019}}\n\n===Community colleges===\n{{main|Community colleges in the United States}}\n{{anchor|Two-year college}}\nCommunity colleges are often [[two-year college]]s. They have [[open admissions]], usually with lower tuition fees than other state or private schools.{{Citation needed|date=August 2017}} Graduates earn [[associate's degree]]s, such as an [[Associate of Arts]] (A.A.). Many students earn an AA at a two-year institution before [[Transfer admissions in the United States|transferring]] to a four-year institution to complete studies for a bachelor's degree.<ref name=NYT-Frerking-042207>Beth Frerking, [https://www.nytimes.com/2007/04/22/education/edlife/bestccs.html Community Colleges: For Achievers, a New Destination], ''The New York Times'', April 22, 2007.</ref> Graduates of such programs, particularly in the engineering technologies, can earn more than $50,000 per year.<ref>{{cite web\n | url =https://cew.georgetown.edu/cew-reports/subba/\n | title =The Overlooked Value of Certificates and Associate's Degrees: What Students Need to Know Before They Go to College\n | last =Carnevale\n | first =Anthony\n | date =January 2020\n | website =Center on Education and the Workforce\n | publisher =Georgetown University\n | access-date =28 January 2020\n | quote =This report examines the labor-market value of associate\u2019s degrees and certificate programs, finding that field of study especially influences future earnings for these programs since they are tightly linked with specific occupations. }}</ref>\n\nAccording to [[National Student Clearinghouse]] data, community college enrollment has dropped by 1.6 million students since its peak year of 2010\u201311. In 2017, 88% of community colleges surveyed were facing declining enrollments.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2016/10/18/community-colleges-examining-low-and-stagnant-enrollments|title=Community colleges examining low and stagnant enrollments|website=Insidehighered.com|access-date=October 18, 2017}}</ref> A ''[[The New York Times]]'' report in 2017 suggested that of the nation's 18 million undergraduates, 40% were attending community college; of these students, 62% were attending community college full-time, 40% of them worked at least 30 hours a week or more, and more than half lived at home to save money.<ref name=twsNYT8448>Gail O. Mellow, August 28, 2017, The New York Times, [https://www.nytimes.com/2017/08/28/opinion/community-college-misconception.html The Biggest Misconception About Today\u2019s College Students], Retrieved August 28, 2017</ref>\n\nThe [[College Promise]] program, which exists in several forms in 24 states, is an effort to encourage community college enrollment.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kanter |first1=Martha |last2=Armstrong |first2=Andra |title=The College Promise: Transforming the Lives of Community College Students |url=https://www.league.org/istream-other/college-promise-transforming-lives-community-college-students |website=League for Innovation in the Commnity College |accessdate=6 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Liberal arts colleges===\nFour-year institutions emphasizing the [[liberal arts]] are [[Liberal arts colleges in the United States|liberal arts colleges]]. They traditionally emphasize interactive instruction. They are known for being [[Residential college|residential]] and for having smaller enrollment and lower student-to-faculty ratios than universities. Most are [[private school|private]], although there are [[Council of Public Liberal Arts Colleges|public liberal arts colleges]]. Some offer [[alternative education|experimental curricula]], such as [[Hampshire College]], [[Beloit College]], [[Bard College at Simon's Rock]], [[Pitzer College]], [[Sarah Lawrence College]], [[Grinnell College]], [[Bennington College]], [[New College of Florida]], and [[Reed College]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Creative Curriculum |url=https://www.hampshire.edu/sustainable/creative-curriculum |website=Hampshire College |accessdate=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===For-profit colleges===\n{{See also|For-profit higher education in the United States}}\nFor-profit higher education (known as [[for-profit college]] or proprietary education) refers to higher education institutions operated by private, profit-seeking businesses. Students were \"attracted to the programs for their ease of enrollment and help obtaining financial aid,\" but \"disappointed with the poor quality of education....\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.educationdive.com/news/for-profit-online-students-drawn-by-convenience-but-left-disappointed/551721/ |title=For-profit online students drawn by convenience but left 'disappointed' |first=Ben |last=Unglesbee |date=April 1, 2019 |website=EducationDive |access-date=April 2, 2019 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.brookings.edu/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/The-Failings-of-Online-For-profit-Colleges.pdf |title=The Failings of Online For-profit Colleges: Findings from Student Borrower Focus Groups |website=The Brookings Institution |date=March 2019 |first1=Robin |last1=Howarth |first2=Lisa |last2=Stifler |access-date=April 2, 2019 }}</ref> [[University of Phoenix]] has been the largest for-profit college in the US.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://americanradioworks.publicradio.org/features/tomorrows-college/phoenix/story-of-university-of-phoenix.html|title=The Story of the University of Phoenix|first=American Public|last=Media|website=americanradioworks.publicradio.org}}</ref> Since 2010, for-profit colleges have received greater scrutiny from the US government, state Attorneys General, the media, and scholars.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/forprofit-college-probe-expands-1389647449|title=For-Profit College Probe Expands|first1=Stephanie|last1=Armour|first2=Alan|last2=Zibel|date=January 13, 2014|website=Wsj.com|access-date=October 18, 2017}}</ref> Notable business failures include [[Corinthian Colleges]] (2015), [[ITT Educational Services]] (2016), [[Education Management Corporation]] also known as EDMC (2017), and [[Education Corporation of America]] (2018).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2018/12/06/closure-education-corporation-america-raises-questions-about-oversight-and-support|title=Closure of Education Corporation of America raises questions about oversight and support for students|website=www.insidehighered.com}}</ref>\n\n==Funding of universities and colleges==\n[[File:United States Federal College Funding 2017.PNG|thumb|In 2017, the federal contribution amounted to 40 billion dollars. Only 100 schools out of more than 4,000 received 80% of that sum.]]\n\n===Sources of funds===\nUS colleges and universities receive their funds from many sources, including tuition, federal [[Title IV]] funds, state funds, and endowments.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbpp.org/research/state-budget-and-tax/a-lost-decade-in-higher-education-funding|title=A Lost Decade in Higher Education Funding|author=|date=August 22, 2017|website=Center on Budget and Policy Priorities|access-date=April 17, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://pew.org/1G94lXI|title=Federal and State Funding of Higher Education|author=|date=|website=pew.org|access-date=April 17, 2019}}</ref><ref>https://www.acenet.edu/news-room/Documents/Understanding-Endowments-White-Paper.pdf</ref> \n\n====State government====\nThe major source of funding for public institutions of higher education is direct support from the state.  The levels of state support roughly correlate with the population of the state.  For example, with a population nearly 40M, the state of California allocates more than $15B on higher education.  At the other extreme, Wyoming allocates $384M for its 570,000 citizens.<ref>{{https://education.illinoisstate.edu/grapevine/tables/}}</ref>\n\n====Institutional donors and endowments====\n{{main|List of colleges and universities in the United States by endowment}}\nPrivate giving supports both private and public institutions. Gifts come in two forms, current use and endowment. Both types of gifts are usually constrained according to a contract between the donor and the institution.\n\nPrivate institutions tend to be more reliant on private giving.<ref name=nacubo18>{{cite web|url=https://www.nacubo.org/-/media/Nacubo/Documents/research/2018-Endowment-Market-Values--Final.ashx?la=en&hash=31CF91E74EAAB91288E53E2BCD629C35710C1C03|year=2018|title=U.S. and Canadian Institutions Listed by Fiscal Year (FY) 2018 Endowment Market Value and Change* in Endowment Market Value from FY17 to FY18}}</ref>\n* [[Harvard University]] $40.9 billion\n* [[University of Texas]] $30.88 billion\n* [[Princeton University]] $25.9 billion\nAt the other extreme, the HBCU [[Fayetteville State University]], has an endowment of $22M.<ref name=nacubo18/>\n\nPrivate philanthropy can be controversial.  At the University of Maryland, [[Northrop Grumman]] has funded a cybersecurity concentration, designs the curriculum in cybersecurity, provides computers and pays some cost of a new dorm. At Ohio State, [[IBM]] partnered to teach [[big data]] analytics. Murray State University's engineering program was supported by computer companies. The [[College of Nanoscale Science and Engineering]] at State University of New York in Albany, received billions of dollars in private sector investment.<ref>{{cite news|last=Belkin|first=Douglas|title=Corporate Cash Alters University Curricula|url=https://www.wsj.com/news/articles/SB10001424052702303847804579481500497963552|access-date=April 23, 2014|newspaper=WSJ|date=April 7, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Student costs and funding===\nIn 2016, average estimated annual student costs (excluding books) were $16,757 at public institutions, $43,065 at private nonprofit institutions, and $23,776 at private for-profit institutions. Between 2006 and 2016, prices at public colleges and universities rose 34 percent above inflation, and prices at private nonprofit institutions rose 26 percent above inflation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nces.ed.gov/programs/digest/d16/ |title=Digest of Education Statistics, 2016 - Introduction |publisher=Nces.ed.gov |date= |access-date=January 2, 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Main Building at The University of Texas at Austin.jpg|right|thumb|The Main Building on the campus of the [[University of Texas at Austin]]]]\nStudents receive [[scholarships]], [[student loan]]s, or [[Grant (money)|grants]] to offset costs [[Out-of-pocket expenses|out-of-pocket]]. Several states offer scholarships that allow students to attend free of tuition or at lower cost, for example the [[HOPE Scholarship]] in [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]] and the [[Bright Futures Scholarship Program]] in [[Florida]]. Some private colleges and universities offer full need-based financial aid, so that admitted students only have to pay as much as their families can afford (based on the university's assessment of their income).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://yale.edu/tuba/finaid/finaid-information/how-need-based-aid-works.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=March 14, 2015 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150312202328/http://yale.edu/tuba/finaid/finaid-information/how-need-based-aid-works.html |archive-date=March 12, 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.usnews.com/education/best-colleges/paying-for-college/articles/2014/09/15/colleges-and-universities-that-claim-to-meet-full-financial-need |title=Archived copy |access-date=August 29, 2017 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151030162631/http://www.usnews.com/education/best-colleges/paying-for-college/articles/2014/09/15/colleges-and-universities-that-claim-to-meet-full-financial-need |archive-date=October 30, 2015 }}</ref><ref>[https://www.npr.org/2013/01/09/168889785/elite-colleges-struggle-to-recruit-smart-low-income-kids Elite Colleges Struggle To Recruit Smart, Low-Income Kids] January 9, 2013, Shankar Vedantam, NPR.org</ref> In most cases, the barrier of entry for students who require financial aid is set higher, a practice called need-aware admissions. Universities with exceptionally large endowments may combine need-based financial aid with [[need-blind admission]], in which students who require financial aid have equal chances to those who do not.{{citation needed|date=March 2015}}\n\nFinancial assistance comes in two major forms: grant programs and loan programs. Grant programs consist of money the student receives to pay for higher education that does not need to be paid back; loan programs consist of money the student receives to pay for school that must be paid back. Public higher education institutions (which are partially funded through state government appropriation) and private higher education institutions (which are funded exclusively through tuition and private donations) offer grant and loan financial assistance programs. Grants to attend public schools are distributed through federal and state governments, and through the schools themselves; grants to attend private schools are distributed through the school itself (independent organizations, such as charities or corporations also offer grants that can be applied to both public and private higher education institutions).<ref name=\"College Board 2007\">{{cite book|title=Meeting College Costs: A Workbook for Families|year=2007|publisher=College Board|location=New York|author=College Board|chapter=3}}</ref> Loans can be obtained publicly through government sponsored loan programs or privately through independent lending institutions.\n\n====Grants, scholarships, loans and work study programs====\n{{main|Student loans in the United States}}\nGrant programs and work study programs are divided into two major categories: [[Student financial aid in the United States#Need-based aid|Need-based financial awards]] and [[Student financial aid in the United States#Merit-based aid|merit-based financial awards]]. Most state governments provide need-based scholarship programs, while a few also offer merit-based aid.<ref name=levitz2012>{{Citation |author=Jennifer Levitz |author2=Scott Thurm |date=December 20, 2012 |title=Shift to Merit Scholarships Stirs Debate |newspaper=The Wall Street Journal |pages=A1;A16 }}</ref> Several need-based grants are provided through the federal government based on information provided on a student's [[Free Application for Federal Student Aid]] or FAFSA.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fafsa.ed.gov|title=Free Application for Federal Student Aid|website=FAFSA on the Web}}</ref> The federal [[Pell Grant]] is a need-based grant available from the federal government. The federal government had two other grants that were a combination of need-based and merit-based: the Academic Competitiveness Grant, and the National SMART Grant, but the SMART grant was abolished in 2011 with the last grant awarded in June 2011. In order to receive one of these grants a student must be eligible for the Pell Grant, meet specific academic requirements, and be a US citizen.<ref name=\"College Board 2007\"/>\n\nEligibility for work study programs is also determined by information collected on the student's FAFSA.<ref name=\"College Board 2007\"/>\n\nMany companies offer tuition reimbursement plans for their employees, to make benefits package more attractive, to upgrade the skill levels and to increase retention.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Flaherty Manchester | first1 = Colleen | year = 2012 | title = General human capital and employee mobility: How tuition reimbursement increases retention through sorting and participation | url = | journal = Industrial & Labor Relations Review | volume = 65 | issue = 4| pages = 951\u2013974 | doi=10.1177/001979391206500408}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, total student loans exceeded consumer credit card debt for the first time in history.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/01/09/brian-mcbride-paying-off-26500-in-debt_n_2441339.html|title=Paying Off $26,500 In Debt In Two Years: How Brian McBride Did It|publisher=HUFF POST|access-date=July 26, 2013|first=Tyler|last=Kingkade|date=January 9, 2013}}</ref> In late 2016, the total estimated US student loan debt exceeded $1.4 trillion.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.marketwatch.com/story/every-second-americans-get-buried-under-another-3055-in-student-loan-debt-2015-06-10|title=Watch America's student-loan debt grow $2,726 every second|first=Jillian|last=Berman|website=Marketwatch.com|access-date=October 18, 2017}}</ref>\n\nStudent loans can be divided into two categories: federal student loans and private student loans.\nFederal student loans may be: \n*[[Stafford Loan|subsidized Stafford Loans]]\n*[[Stafford Loan|unsubsidized Stafford Loans]]\n*[[Federal Direct Student Loan Program|Direct Loans]]\n*[[PLUS Loan]]s \nA student's eligibility for any of these loans, as well as the amount of the loan itself is determined by information on the student's [[FAFSA]]. \nThe  former [[Federal Perkins Loan]] program expired in 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://studentloans.net/perkins-loan-program-expires/|title=Perkins Loan Program Expires After Extension Bill is Blocked |date=October 3, 2017|publisher=The Student Loan Report}}</ref>\n\n==Statistics==\n\nThe [[National Center for Education Statistics]] (NCES) and [[National Student Clearinghouse]], show that college enrollment has declined since a peak in 2010\u201311 and is projected to continue declining or be stagnant for the next two decades.<ref name=\"insidehighered.com1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/admissions/article/2018/01/08/new-book-argues-most-colleges-are-about-face-significant-decline|title=New book argues most colleges are about to face significant decline in prospective students - Inside Higher Ed|website=www.insidehighered.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2018/05/25/614315950/why-is-undergraduate-college-enrollment-declining|title=Why Is Undergraduate College Enrollment Declining?|website=NPR.org}}</ref><ref name=\"nces.ed.gov\">{{cite web |url=https://nces.ed.gov/pubs2018/2018144.pdf |title=The Condition of Education |date=May 2018 |website=National Center for Education Studies |access-date=April 2, 2019 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/quicktakes/2018/05/31/intensive-english-enrollments-us-drop-20|title=Intensive English Enrollments in U.S. Drop 20% - Inside Higher Ed|website=www.insidehighered.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://studentclearinghouse.org/nscblog/fall-2018-overall-postsecondary-enrollments-decreased-1-7-percent-from-last-fall/|title=Fall 2018 Overall Postsecondary Enrollments Decreased 1.7 Percent from Last Fall|first=N. S. C.|last=Blog|date=December 13, 2018|website=studentclearinghouse.org|access-date=March 21, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"ed.gov\">{{cite web |url=https://nces.ed.gov/pubs2019/2019001.pdf |title=Projections of Education Statistics to 2027 |date=February 2019 |website=National Center for Education Studies |access-date=April 2, 2019 }}</ref>\n\nUS educational statistics are provided by the [[National Center for Education Statistics]] (NCES), part of the [[US Department of Education|Department of Education]]. The number of [[Title IV|Title IV-eligible]], degree-granting institutions peaked at 4,726 in 2012 with 3,026 4-year institutions and 1,700 2-year institutions: by 2016\u201317, the total had declined to 4,360 institutions with only 2832 4-year institutions and 1528 2-year institutions existing.\n<ref name=institutions>{{cite web|url=https://nces.ed.gov/programs/digest/d17/tables/dt17_317.10.asp?current=yes|title=Degree-granting postsecondary institutions, by control and level of institution: Selected years, 1949-50 through 2016-17|publisher=NCES|access-date=December 15, 2018}}</ref>\nThe enrollment at postsecondary institutions, participating in Title IV, peaked at just over 21.5 million students in 2010.\nl<ref name=enrollment>{{cite web|url=https://nces.ed.gov/programs/digest/d17/tables/dt17_303.20.asp|publisher=NCES|title=Total fall enrollment in all postsecondary institutions participating in Title IV programs and annual percentage change in enrollment, by degree-granting status and control of institution: 1995 through 2016|access-date=December 15, 2018}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!rowspan=2| Year !!colspan=2| Fall enrollment<ref name=enrollment/> !!colspan=3| Degree-granting institutions<ref name=institutions/>\n|-\n!(all postsecondary)!!(degree-granting)!!(total)!!(4-year)!!(2-year)\n|-\n| 2010-11 || 21,591,742 || 21,019,438 || 4,599 || 2,870 || 1,729\n|-\n| 2011-12 || 21,573,798 || 21,010,590 || 4,706 || 2,968 || 1,738\n|-\n| 2012-13 || 21,148,181 || 20,644,478 || 4,726 || 3,026 || 1,700\n|-\n| 2013-14 || 20,848,050 || 20,376,677 || 4,724 || 3,039 || 1,685\n|-\n| 2014-15 || 20,664,180 || 20,209,092 || 4,627 || 3,011 || 1,616\n|-\n| 2015-16 || 20,400,164 || 19,988,204 || 4,583 || 3,004 || 1,579\n|-\n| 2016-17 || 20,224,069 || 19,841,014 || 4,360 || 2,832 || 1,528\n|}\n\nA US Department of Education [[Longitudinal study|longitudinal survey]] of 15,000 high school students in 2002 and 2012, found that 84% of the 27-year-old students had some college education, but only 34% achieved a bachelor's degree or higher; 79% owe some money for college and 55% owe more than $10,000; college dropouts were three times more likely to be unemployed than those who finished college; 40% spent some time unemployed and 23% were unemployed for six months or more; and 79% earned less than $40,000 per year.<ref name=\"NCES 2014\">{{cite web|title=Education Longitudinal Study of 2002 (ELS: 2002): A First Look at 2002 High School Sophomores 10 Years Later First Look|url=http://nces.ed.gov/pubs2014/2014363.pdf|work=NCES 2014-363|publisher=U.S. Department of Education|access-date=May 23, 2014|date=January 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"AtlanticMonthly\">Jordan Weissmann, Atlantic Monthly, January 14, 2014, [https://www.theatlantic.com/business/archive/2014/01/highly-educated-highly-indebted-the-lives-of-todays-27-year-olds-in-charts/283263/ Highly Educated, Highly Indebted: The Lives of Today's 27-Year-Olds, In Charts: A new study by the Department of Education offers up a statistical picture of young-adult life in the wake of the Great Recession], Accessed January 26, 2014</ref>\n\n===Declining enrollment, mergers, and campus closures===\nFalling birth rates result in fewer people graduating from high school. The number of high school graduates grew 30% from 1995 to 2013, then peaked at 3.5\u2009million; projections show it holding at that level in the next decade.<ref>see [http://knocking.wiche.edu/reports/2017/3/22/full-report \"Knocking at the College Door, 9th Edition: Projections of High School Graduates\" Dec 6, 2016  ].</ref> Liberal arts programs have been declining for decades. From 1967 to 2018, college students majoring in the liberal arts declined from 20 percent to 5 percent.<ref name=\"hechingerreport.org\">{{cite web|url=https://hechingerreport.org/liberal-arts-face-uncertain-future-at-nations-universities/|title=Liberal arts face uncertain future at nation's universities|date=June 4, 2018}}</ref>\n\nSince 2011, there has been a significant decline in the number of students enrolled in postsecondary education in the United States. That is more than 2 million people.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/michaeltnietzel/2019/12/16/college-enrollment-declines-again-its-down-more-than-two-million-students-in-this-decade/|title=College Enrollment Declines Again. It's Down More Than Two Million Students In This Decade.|last=Nietzel|first=Michael T.|date=16 December 2019|website=Forbes|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-26}}</ref>  In the fall of 2019, according to the ''National Student Clearinghouse Research Center'', enrollment declined 1.3% from 2018, approximately 231,000 less students.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nscresearchcenter.org/current-term-enrollment-estimates-2019/|title=Current Term Enrollment Estimates - Fall 2019|last=|first=|date=2019-12-16|website=National Student Clearinghouse Research Center|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-26}}</ref> Researchers hypothesize that the primary factors leading to this drop in enrollment are low birth rates over the last couple decades, a more successful economy, and the increasing cost of postsecondary education coupled with a decrease in financial aid and student debt.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/michaeltnietzel/2019/12/16/college-enrollment-declines-again-its-down-more-than-two-million-students-in-this-decade/|title=College Enrollment Declines Again. It's Down More Than Two Million Students In This Decade.|last=Nietzel|first=Michael T.|date=16 December 2019|website=Forbes|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2019/12/16/787909495/fewer-students-are-going-to-college-heres-why-that-matters|title=Fewer Students Are Going To College. Here's Why That Matters|last=|first=|date=|website=NPR.org|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-26}}</ref> Some potential students are also questioning the value of a postsecondary education and whether it is necessary to gain employment.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/michaeltnietzel/2019/12/16/college-enrollment-declines-again-its-down-more-than-two-million-students-in-this-decade/|title=College Enrollment Declines Again. It's Down More Than Two Million Students In This Decade.|last=Nietzel|first=Michael T.|date=16 December 2019|website=Forbes|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2019/12/16/787909495/fewer-students-are-going-to-college-heres-why-that-matters|title=Fewer Students Are Going To College. Here's Why That Matters|last=|first=|date=|website=NPR.org|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-26}}</ref> In 2018, the [[National Center for Education Statistics]] projected stagnant enrollment patterns until at least 2027.<ref name=\"nces.ed.gov\"/> Demographer Nathan Grawe projected that lower birth rates following the [[Great Recession]] of 2008 would result in a 15 percent enrollment loss, beginning in 2026.<ref name=\"insidehighered.com1\"/>\n\nIn 2019, the National Center for Education Statistics continued to project that higher education enrollment would remain stagnant, but white enrollment would drop 8 percent from 2016 to 2027. The report projected black enrollment to increase by 6 percent, Hispanic enrollment to increase 14 percent, Asian/Pacific Islander enrollment to increase 7 percent, and American Indian/Alaska Native enrollment to decrease 9 percent during the same period.<ref name=\"ed.gov\"/> In March 2019, [[Moody's]] warned that enrollment declines could lead to more financial problems for the higher education industry.<ref>https://www.educationdive.com/news/moodys-slow-enrollment-gains-raise-colleges-financial-risk/549960/</ref> In a 2019 survey by ''[[Inside Higher Ed]]'', nearly one in seven college presidents said their campus could close or merge within five years.<ref name=\"auto8\">{{cite web|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/survey/2019-survey-college-and-university-presidents|title=2019 Survey of College and University Presidents - Inside Higher Ed|author=|date=|website=www.InsideHigherEd.com|access-date=March 29, 2019}}</ref> In April 2019, Connecticut presented a plan to consolidate their community colleges with their accreditor.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2019/04/17/connecticut-community-colleges-faculty-and-administration-odds-over-proposed|title=Connecticut community colleges faculty and administration at odds over proposed consolidation|author=|date=April 17, 2019|website=www.InsideHigherEd.com|access-date=April 25, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn \"The Higher Education Apocalypse\", ''[[U.S. News & World Report]]'' education reporter Lauren Camera speculated that recent closings of schools in New England might be the beginning of a rash of college closures.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://www.usnews.com/news/education-news/articles/2019-03-22/college-closings-signal-start-of-a-crisis-in-higher-education |title=The Higher Education Apocalypse |magazine=U.S. News & World Report |first=Lauren |last=Camera |date=March 22, 2019 |access-date=April 2, 2019 }}</ref> An analysis of federal data from ''[[The Chronicle of Higher Education]]'' shows \"about half a million students have been displaced by college closures, which together shuttered more than 1,200 campuses.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.chronicle.com/interactives/20190404-ForProfit|title=How America's College-Closure Crisis Leaves Families Devastated|author=|date=April 4, 2019|website=The Chronicle of Higher Education|access-date=April 6, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Admission process==\n{{Main|College admissions in the United States}}{{Further|Transfer admissions in the United States}}\nStudents can apply to some colleges using the [[Common Application]]. With a few exceptions, most undergraduate colleges and universities maintain the policy that students are to be admitted to (or rejected from) the entire college, not to a particular [[Academic department|department]] or [[academic major|major]]. (This is unlike college admissions in many European countries, as well as graduate admissions.) Some students, rather than being rejected, are \"wait-listed\" for a particular college and may be admitted if another student who was admitted decides not to attend the college or university. The five major parts of admission are [[ACT (test)|ACT]]/[[SAT]] scores, [[grade point average]], college application, essay, and [[letters of recommendation]]. The SAT's usefulness in the admissions process is controversial.<ref>{{Citation\n | last =Buckley\n | first =Jack\n | last2 =Letukas\n | first2 =Lynn\n | last3 =Wildavsky\n | first3 =Ben\n | title =Measuring Success: Testing, Grades, and the Future of College Admissions\n | place =Baltimore\n | publisher =Johns Hopkins University Press\n | year =2017\n | page =344\n | url =https://jhupbooks.press.jhu.edu/content/measuring-success\n | archive-url =\n | archive-date =\n | isbn =9781421424965\n }}</ref><ref>{{Citation| last =Coates| first =Ken| last2 =Morrison| first2 =Bill| title =What to Consider If You're Considering College: New Rules for Education and Employment| publisher =Dundurn| year =2015| page =280| isbn =978-1459723726}}</ref>\n\n===Legacies and large donors===\nAdmissions at elite schools include preferences to alumni and large investors.<ref name=\"auto4\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/education/archive/2019/03/college-admissions-scandal-fbi-targets-wealthy-parents/584695/|title=Why the College-Admissions Scandal Is So Absurd|first=Alia|last=Wong|date=March 12, 2019|website=The Atlantic|access-date=March 21, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.propublica.org/article/college-admission-bribe-rich-parents-ivy-league-how-to|title=How the Rich Really Play, 'Who Wants To Be An Ivy Leaguer?'|first=Daniel|last=Golden|date=March 12, 2019|website=ProPublica|access-date=March 21, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://politi.co/2HvLde0|title=Admissions scandal reveals why America's elite colleges are under fire|first=Benjamin|last=Wermund|date=|website=POLITICO|access-date=March 21, 2019}}</ref> Legislators have asked for transparency with donors and college admissions, but there are several groups that oppose it.<ref>https://www.insidehighered.com/admissions/article/2019/06/10/senator-offers-legislation-respond-admissions-scandal</ref> ''[[Inside Higher Ed]]'''s 2018 survey of college admissions directors found that 42 percent of private colleges and universities used legacy status as a factor in admissions decisions.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/admissions/article/2019/04/22/study-shows-significant-impact-legacy-status-admissions-and-applicants|title=Study shows significant impact of legacy status in admissions, and that the applicants have been strong - Inside Higher Ed|author=|date=April 22, 2019|website=www.InsideHigherEd.com|access-date=April 25, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==International study and student exchange==\n[[File:Low Memorial Library Columbia University NYC.jpg|thumb|right|300px|[[Columbia University]] Low Memorial Library]]\n<!---hokey title needs changing--->\n\nIn 2016\u201317, 332,727 US students studied abroad for credit. Most took place in Europe, with 40 percent of students studying in five countries: the United Kingdom, Italy, Spain, France, and Germany.<ref>https://www.nafsa.org/Policy_and_Advocacy/Policy_Resources/Policy_Trends_and_Data/Trends_in_U_S__Study_Abroad/</ref> The US is the most popular country in the world for attracting students from other countries, according to [[UNESCO]], with 16% of all international students going to the US (the next highest is the UK with 11%).<ref name=\"uis.unesco.org\">{{cite web|url=http://www.uis.unesco.org/EDUCATION/Pages/international-student-flow-viz.aspx|title=Global Flow of Tertiary-Level Students|publisher=UNESCO Institute for Statistics|year=2012|access-date=October 7, 2013}}</ref> 671,616 foreign students enrolled in American colleges in 2008\u201309.<ref name=\"uis.unesco.org\"/><ref>{{cite news| first=Mary Beth | last=Marklein | title=More U.S. students going abroad, and vice versa | url=https://www.usatoday.com/news/education/2009-11-16-opendoors16_ST_N.htm | newspaper=USA Today | pages= 5D | date=November 16, 2009 }}</ref> This figure rose to 723,277 in 2010\u201311. The largest number, 157,558, came from China.<ref>{{Cite news | first=Mary Beth | last=Marklein | title=More foreign students in USA | url=https://www.usatoday.com/news/education/story/2011-11-13/foreign-students-boost-usa-economy/51188560/1| work= | publisher=Florida Today | location=Melbourne, Florida | pages= 4A | date=November 14, 2010 | id= | access-date=}}</ref><!---hard copy does not match soft copy but are the same article internally ---> According to ''[[Uni in the USA]]'', despite \"exorbitant\" costs of US universities, higher education in America remains attractive to international students due to \"generous subsidies and financial aid packages that enable students from even the most disadvantaged backgrounds to attend the college of their dreams\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uniintheusa.com/how-why/paying-for-us-uni/609/can-i-afford-it|title=Paying for US uni.|publisher=UNI. in the USA and Beyond|year=2012|access-date=October 7, 2013|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130923091612/http://www.uniintheusa.com/how-why/paying-for-us-uni/609/can-i-afford-it|archive-date=September 23, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Government coordination==\n\n=== Coordination institutions ===\nEvery state has an entity designed to promote coordination and collaboration between higher education institutions. A few are listed: [[Alabama Commission on Higher Education]],\n[[California Postsecondary Education Commission]],\n[[Texas Higher Education Coordinating Board]],\n[[Washington State Higher Education Coordinating Board]],\n[[The Georgia Department of Technical and Adult Education]].\n\n==Academic labor and adjunctification==\n{{Main|Adjunct professors in North America}}\n\nUntil the mid-1970s, when federal expenditures for higher education fell, there were routinely more tenure-track jobs than Ph.D. graduates. In the 1980s and 1990s there were significant changes in the economics of academic life. \nDespite rising tuition rates and growing university revenues, professorial positions were replaced with poorly paid [[Adjunct professors in North America|adjunct]] positions and graduate-student labor.<ref>{{cite news|title=The Case of the Vanishing Full-Time Professor|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/01/03/education/edlife/03strategy-t.html|access-date=December 12, 2012 | work=The New York Times|first=Samantha|last=Stainburn|date=January 3, 2010}}</ref>\n\nWith academic institutions producing Ph.D.s in greater numbers than the number of tenure-track positions they intended to create, [[Academic administration#United States|administrators]] were cognizant of the economic effects of this arrangement. Sociologist [[Stanley Aronowitz]] wrote: \"Basking in the plenitude of qualified and credentialed instructors, many university administrators see the time when they can once again make tenure a rare privilege, awarded only to the most faithful and to those whose services are in great demand\".<ref>Aronowitz, Stanley. ''The Knowledge Factory: Dismantling the Corporate University and Creating True Higher Learning'', p. 76. {{ISBN|0807031232}}.</ref> Aggravating the problem, those few academics who do achieve tenure are often determined to stay put as long as possible, refusing lucrative incentives to retire early.<ref>{{cite web\n | url =http://hechingerreport.org/aging-faculty-who-wont-leave-thwart-universities-attempts-to-cut-costs/\n | title =Aging faculty who won't leave thwart universities' attempts to cut costs\n | last =Marcus\n | first =Jon\n | date =October 9, 2015\n | website =Hechinger Report\n | publisher =Teachers College at Columbia University\n | access-date =May 4, 2018\n | quote =Protected by tenure that prevents them from being dismissed without cause, and with no mandatory retirement age, a significant proportion of university faculty isn\u2019t going anywhere. }}</ref>\n\nAronowitz ascribed this problem to the economic restructuring of academia as a whole, stating that \"The idea of an academic \"job market\" based on the balance of supply and demand in an open competitive arena is a fiction whose effect is to persuade the candidate that (he or she) simply lost out because of bad luck or lack of talent. The truth is otherwise.\"<ref>Aronowitz, ''The Knowledge Factory'' 75\u201376. {{ISBN missing}} year?</ref>}}\nIn 2017, 17% of faculty was tenured. 89% of adjunct professors worked at more than one job. An adjunct was paid an average of $2,700 for a single course. 31% of the faculty lived below the poverty level. While student-faculty ratios remained the same since 1975, administrator-student ratio went from 1\u201384 to 1\u201368. student-professional staff ratios fell from 50:1 to 21:1. The money that colleges received went into administration and staff and not teaching.<ref name=ft170219>{{Cite news | first=Glenn Harlan | last=Reynolds | title=President Trump should take pity on poor PhD | url=http://www.floridatoday.com/story/opinion/2017/02/18/trump-should-pity-poor-phd/98030172/| newspaper=Florida Today | location=Melbourne, Florida| pages= 19A | date=February 19, 2017 | access-date=February 20, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, the [[American Association of University Professors]] (AAUP) reported that 73 percent of all faculty positions were filled by adjuncts.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aaup.org/news/data-snapshot-contingent-faculty-us-higher-ed|title=Data Snapshot: Contingent Faculty in US Higher Ed - AAUP|website=www.aaup.org}}</ref>\n\nAdjunct organizations include the Coalition for Contingent (COCAL), the New Faculty Majority, and [[SEIU]] Faculty Forward.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cocalinternational.org/aboutus.html|title=COCAL|website=cocalinternational.org}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newfacultymajority.info/history-and-foundational-principles/|title=History - New Faculty Majority}}</ref>\nThe [[American Federation of Teachers]] (AFT) and [[Teamsters Union]] have also organized contingent academic labor.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://aftvoices.org/why-i-would-go-on-strike-i-cant-afford-to-give-students-the-attention-they-deserve-23e078dbb75|title=Why I'm ready to walk out: I can't afford to give students the attention they deserve|last=AFTVoicesoncampus|date=April 16, 2018|website=AFT Voices}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.njspotlight.com/stories/18/12/06/fed-up-rutgers-faculty-protest-slow-pace-of-contract-talks-threaten-to-strike/|title='Fed Up' Rutgers Faculty Protest Slow Contract Talks, Threaten to Strike - NJ Spotlight|website=www.njspotlight.com}}</ref>\n\n==Athletics==\n{{main|College athletics in the United States}}\n\n[[College athletics]] in the US is a two-tiered system. The first tier includes sports sanctioned by one of the collegiate sport governing bodies. Some of these collegiate sports governing organizations like the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association]] (NCAA) are umbrella [[non-profit organization]]s that govern multiple sports. Additionally, the first tier is characterized by selective participation, since only the elite programs in their sport are able to participate; some colleges offer [[athletic scholarship]]s to intercollegiate sports competitors. The second tier includes [[intramural]] and recreational sports clubs, which are available to more of the student body. Competition between student clubs from different colleges, not organized by and therefore not representing the institutions or their faculties, may also be called \"intercollegiate\" athletics or simply college sports.<ref>{{cite book|last=Rosandich|first=Thomas|title=Collegiate Sports Programs: A Comparative Analysis|page=476|publisher=Education|date=2002}}</ref>\n\nThe largest collegiate sport governing body in the first tier is the NCAA, which regulates athletes of 1,268 institutions across the US and Canada. The NCAA uses a three-division system of [[NCAA Division I|Division I]], [[NCAA Division II|Division II]], and [[NCAA Division III|Division III]]. Division I and Division II schools can offer scholarships to athletes for playing a sport, while Division III schools cannot offer any athletic scholarships.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ncaapublications.com/productdownloads/D313.pdf |title=Bylaw 15.01.3 Institutional Financial Aid |work=2012\u201313 NCAA Division III Manual |publisher=NCAA |page=107 |access-date=December 19, 2012}}</ref> Division I schools, which generally are larger than either Division II or III institutions, must further meet additional requirements: among them, they must field teams in at least seven sports for men and seven for women or six for men and eight for women, with at least two team sports for each gender.<ref name=\"NCAA Division Differences\">{{cite web |url=https://www.ncaa.org/wps/wcm/connect/public/ncaa/about+the+ncaa/who+we+are/differences+among+the+divisions/division+i/about+division+i |title=The Official Web Site of the NCAA |publisher=NCAA.org |access-date=January 4, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120117032949/http://www.ncaa.org/wps/wcm/connect/public/ncaa/about+the+ncaa/who+we+are/differences+among+the+divisions/division+i/about+division+i |archivedate=January 17, 2012 |df=mdy }}</ref> Each division is then further divided into several [[athletic conference|conferences]] for regional league play. The names of these conferences, such as the [[Ivy League]], may be used to refer to their respective schools as a group beyond a sports context.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://etcweb.princeton.edu/CampusWWW/Companion/ivy_league.html |title=Princeton Campus Guide \u2013 Ivy League|access-date=April 26, 2007}}</ref>\n\nCollege sports are popular on regional and national scales, at times competing with professional championships for prime broadcast, print coverage. In most states, the person with the highest taxpayer-provided base salary is a public college football or basketball coach. This does not include coaches at private colleges.<ref>{{cite web\n | url =https://thebestschools.org/magazine/highest-paid-college-coaches/\n | title =The 25 Highest-Paid College Coaches\n | last =Rich\n | first =Bobby\n | website =The Quad\n | quote =We focus solely on what universities pay their coaches as their base salary, and do not include bonuses or any outside income. }}</ref> The average university sponsors at least 20 different sports and offers a wide variety of intramural sports. There are approximately 400,000 men and women [[Student athlete|student-athletes]] that participate in sanctioned athletics each year.<ref>{{cite book|last=Rosandich|first=Thomas|title=Collegiate Sports Programs: A Comparative Analysis|page=474|publisher=Education|date=2002}}</ref>\n\n==Issues confronting higher education in the United States==\n{{main|Issues in higher education in the United States}}\nEntrance routes and procedures for choosing a college or university, their rankings and the financial value of degrees are being discussed. This leads to discussions on socioeconomic status and race ethnicity and gender.\nFrom the student perspective, financial issues include college affordability,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pewresearch.org/fact-tank/2018/10/22/more-in-u-s-see-drug-addiction-college-affordability-and-sexism-as-very-big-national-problems/|title=More in U.S. see drug addiction, college affordability and sexism as 'very big' national problems|date=October 22, 2018|website=PewResearch.org|access-date=April 25, 2019}}</ref> the wide ranges of [[remuneration]] and [[underemployment]] among the various degrees,<ref>{{cite web | url =https://www.bls.gov/ooh/ | title =Occupational Outlook Handbook | website =Bureau of Labor Statistics | publisher =Department of Labor}}</ref><ref>{{citation|url=https://www.newyorkfed.org/research/college-labor-market/index.html|title=The Labor Market for Recent College Graduates|publisher=Federal Reserve Bank of New York}}</ref><ref>{{Citation | last =Carnevale | first =Anthony | last2 =Cheah | first2 =Ban | title =Five Rules of the College and Career Game | publisher =Georgetown University | year =2018 | url =https://cew.georgetown.edu/cew-reports/5rules/ | access-date =May 16, 2018 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url =https://www.burning-glass.com/research-project/underemployment/ | title =Underemployment: Research on the Long-Term Impact on Careers | date =October 2018 | publisher =Burning Glass Technologies and the Strada Institute for the Future of Work | access-date =November 22, 2018}}</ref> rising tuition and increasing [[student loan debt]],<ref>Riley Griffin, [https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-10-17/the-student-loan-debt-crisis-is-about-to-get-worse \"The Student Loan Debt Crisis Is About to Get Worse: The next generation of graduates will include more borrowers who may never be able to repay.\" ''Bloomberg'' October 17, 2018]</ref> [[austerity]] in state and local spending, the [[Adjunct professors in North America|adjunctification of academic labor]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.chronicle.com/article/Straight-Talk-About/150881|title=Straight Talk About 'Adjunctification'|first=Rob|last=Jenkins|date=December 15, 2014|access-date=April 17, 2019|via=The Chronicle of Higher Education}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2019/04/16/herb-childress-discusses-his-new-book-adjunct-underclass|title=Herb Childress discusses his new book, 'The Adjunct Underclass'|author=|date=|website=www.insidehighered.com|access-date=April 17, 2019}}</ref>\nstudent poverty and hunger,<ref name=\"theatlantic.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/education/archive/2016/01/the-hidden-hunger-on-college-campuses/424047/|title=The Gravity of the Hunger Problem on College Campuses|first=Laura|last=McKenna|date=January 14, 2016|website=The Atlantic}}</ref> along with [[credentialism and educational inflation]].<ref>{{cite web | url =https://wp.nyu.edu/dispatch/2017/11/17/the-curse-of-credentialism/ | title =The Curse of Credentialism | date =17 November 2017 | website =The NYU Dispatch | access-date =21 July 2019 | quote =Credentialism, or degree inflation, as it is sometimes referred to, has been a growing problem globally for the better part of the last decade. }}</ref>\n\n==Interest groups==\nInterest groups in US higher education include philanthropic foundations, trade unions, trade associations, think tanks, and businesses associated with higher education.<ref name=\"Ness et al 2015\">{{cite book |doi=10.1007/978-3-319-12835-1_4 |chapter=Interest Groups and State Policy for Higher Education: New Conceptual Understandings and Future Research Directions |title=Higher Education: Handbook of Theory and Research |volume=30 |pages=151\u2013186 |year=2015 |last1=Ness |first1=Erik C. |last2=Tandberg |first2=David A. |last3=McLendon |first3=Michael K. |isbn=978-3-319-12834-4 }}</ref> Philanthropic organizations include the [[Bill and Melinda Gates Foundation]], the [[Walton Family Foundation]], and the [[Charles Koch Foundation]]. Trade unions tied to higher education include the [[American Association of University Professors]], [[American Federation of Teachers]], and [[Service Employees International Union]].\nTrade associations: include the [[American Council on Education]], [[American Association of Community Colleges]], [[American Association of State Colleges and Universities]], and [[Association of American Universities]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sheeo.org/node/428|title=Higher Education Associations - SHEEO|website=www.sheeo.org|access-date=December 5, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181205103619/http://www.sheeo.org/node/428|archive-date=December 5, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> Think tanks reporting on higher education include the [[Lumina Foundation]], [[Center for American Progress]], [[Brookings Institution]], [[Third Way]], and [[Cato Institute]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://guides.lib.berkeley.edu/c.php?g=496970&p=3427170|title=Library Guides: Non Governmental Organizations (NGOs): Think Tanks |first=Jim|last=Church|website=guides.lib.berkeley.edu}}</ref> Businesses associated with higher education include student loan lenders, student loan debt collectors, academic publishers, and online program management companies. Notable companies include [[Wells Fargo]], [[Discover Financial Services]], [[Navient]], [[Sallie Mae]], [[Pearson Education|Pearson]], and [[Prentice Hall]].<ref name=\"Ness et al 2015\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/digital-learning/article/2018/06/04/shakeout-coming-online-program-management-companies|title=Is a shakeout coming for online program management companies? - Inside Higher Ed|website=www.insidehighered.com}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{div col}}\n* [[Academic ranks in the United States]]\n* [[Association of American Universities]]\n* [[Carnegie Classification of Institutions of Higher Education]]\n* [[College admissions in the United States]]\n* [[Education in the United States]]\n* [[G. I. American Universities]]\n* [[Hispanic-serving institution]]\n* [[Historically black colleges and universities]]\n* [[History of education in the United States]]\n* [[History of education in the United States: Bibliography]]\n* [[Land-grant university]]\n* [[Liberal arts colleges in the United States]]\n* [[