{"title_page": "Bradlee Heckmann", "text_new": "{{Infobox scientist\n| name              = Bradlee L. Heckmann\n| image             = FILE:heckmannA.png\n| nationality       = United States\n| fields            = [[Neuroimmunology]]\n[[Autophagy]]\n[[Alzheimer's Disease]]\n| workplaces        = [[St. Jude Children's Research Hospital]]\n| alma_mater        = Mayo Clinic Coll. of Medicine\n[[University of Kentucky]]\n| thesis_title      = The function and regulation of the G0/G1 Switch Gene 2\n| thesis_url        = https://search.proquest.com/openview/cfe389ce39ce8418e0f84556975e7eeb/1?pq-origsite=gscholar&cbl=18750&diss=y\n| academic_advisors = [[Douglas R. Green]],\nEdmund B. Rucker, III\n| doctoral_advisor  = Jun Liu\n| website           = {{URL|http://www.stjude.org}}\n| other_names       = Brad Heckmann\n| birth_place       = [[Lexington, KY]]\n}}\n  \nBradlee L. Heckmann is an American biologist and neuroimmunologist who currently holds the John H. Sununu Endowed Fellowship<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://orcid.org/0000-0002-3271-7183|title=Bradlee L. Heckmann (0000-0002-3271-7183)|last=ORCID|website=orcid.org|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> in Immunology at [[St. Jude Children's Research Hospital]]. Dr. Heckmann's research is focused on understanding the regulation of inflammatory processes in the central nervous system, with particular emphasis on neurodegenerative diseases including [[Alzheimer's disease|Alzheimer's Disease]]<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Heckmann|first=Bradlee L.|last2=Tummers|first2=Bart|last3=Green|first3=Douglas R.|date=January 2019|title=Crashing the computer: apoptosis vs. necroptosis in neuroinflammation|url=https://www.nature.com/articles/s41418-018-0195-3|journal=Cell Death & Differentiation|language=en|volume=26|issue=1|pages=41\u201352|doi=10.1038/s41418-018-0195-3|issn=1476-5403}}</ref> and the role of the [[autophagy]] machinery in this setting.  \n\n== Education ==\nDr. Heckmann graduated from [[Lexington Catholic High School]] in [[Lexington, Kentucky|Lexington, KY]] prior to attending the [[University of Kentucky]] where he graduated with a Bachelor of Science in Biology. Dr. Heckmann went on to complete his doctoral training in Biochemistry & Molecular Biology at the [[Mayo Clinic College of Medicine and Science|Mayo Clinic College of Medicine]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://search.proquest.com/openview/cfe389ce39ce8418e0f84556975e7eeb/1?pq-origsite=gscholar&cbl=18750&diss=y|title=The function and regulation of the G0/G1 Switch Gene 2 (G0S2) - ProQuest|website=search.proquest.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>. After completing his formal training he joined the laboratory of [[Douglas R. Green|Dr. Douglas R. Green]] at St. Jude as a postdoctoral fellow<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stjude.org/education-training/advanced-training/postdoctoral-fellows.html|title=Postdoctoral Fellows|website=www.stjude.org|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>.\n\n== Research ==\nAfter studying lipid metabolism and components that regulate lipid turnover while at [[Mayo Clinic]], Dr. Heckmann switched his research focus to evaluating the role and regulation of non-canonical [[autophagy]] in the brain<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Heckmann|first=Bradlee L.|last2=Green|first2=Douglas R.|date=2019-03-01|title=LC3-associated phagocytosis at a glance|url=https://jcs.biologists.org/content/132/5/jcs222984|journal=Journal of Cell Science|language=en|volume=132|issue=5|doi=10.1242/jcs.222984|issn=0021-9533|pmid=30787029}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Heckmann|first=Bradlee L.|last2=Boada-Romero|first2=Emilio|last3=Cunha|first3=Larissa D.|last4=Magne|first4=Joelle|last5=Green|first5=Douglas R.|date=2017-11-24|title=LC3-Associated Phagocytosis and Inflammation|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0022283617304187|journal=Journal of Molecular Biology|language=en|volume=429|issue=23|pages=3561\u20133576|doi=10.1016/j.jmb.2017.08.012|issn=0022-2836}}</ref>. These studies ultimately led to Heckmann & [[Douglas R. Green|Green]]'s discovery of a novel form of the [[Endocytosis|endocytic]] trafficking pathway.<ref name=\":0\" /> Heckmann and Green showed that a protein known as [[MAP1LC3B|LC3]] which helps facilitate vesicle trafficking and fusion, most well-known for its role in [[autophagy]], was attached to endosomes that contained [[Amyloid beta|\u03b2-amyloid]]<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Heckmann|first=Bradlee L.|last2=Teubner|first2=Brett J. W.|last3=Tummers|first3=Bart|last4=Boada-Romero|first4=Emilio|last5=Harris|first5=Lacie|last6=Yang|first6=Mao|last7=Guy|first7=Clifford S.|last8=Zakharenko|first8=Stanislav S.|last9=Green|first9=Douglas R.|date=2019-07-25|title=LC3-Associated Endocytosis Facilitates \u03b2-Amyloid Clearance and Mitigates Neurodegeneration in Murine Alzheimer\u2019s Disease|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0092867419306270|journal=Cell|language=en|volume=178|issue=3|pages=536\u2013551.e14|doi=10.1016/j.cell.2019.05.056|issn=0092-8674}}</ref>, a known contributor to Alzheimer's Disease in humans. As such they named the discovery LC3-associated endocytosis (LANDO)<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/robinseatonjefferson/2019/07/22/newly-discovered-cellular-pathway-may-mean-new-approach-for-how-we-treat-alzheimers-and-cancer/|title=Newly Discovered Cellular Pathway May Mean New Approach For How We Treat Alzheimer's And Cancer|last=Jefferson|first=Robin Seaton|website=Forbes|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://blogs.stjude.org/progress/lando-process-possible-ally-against-alzheimers-disease/|title=Lando: Star Wars smuggler or possible ally against Alzheimer\u2019s disease?|last=Hospital|first=About The Author Mary Powers Mary Powers is a member of the Communications Department at St Jude Children\u2019s Research|date=2019-07-25|website=St. Jude Progress Blog - St. Jude Children\u2019s Research Hospital|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.alzforum.org/news/research-news/gently-used-can-recycled-microglia-receptors-prevent-plaque|title=Gently Used: Can Recycled Microglia Receptors Prevent Plaque? {{!}} ALZFORUM|website=www.alzforum.org|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>. Further, they found that abrogation of LC3-associated endocytosis in microglial immune cells of the brain resulted in impaired recycling of cell receptors that recognize \u03b2-amyloid, leading to dramatic increases in inflammatory activation.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nHeckmann and Green were the first to show that loss of the LC3-associated endocytosis pathway in microglia greatly exacerbated the disease pathology of Alzheimer's Disease and that the LANDO pathway appears to be protective against \u03b2-amyloid induced neuroinflammation and neurodegeneration, work recently published in ''[https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0092867419306270?via%3Dihub Cell]''<ref name=\":0\" /> and featured in mainstream media<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.biospace.com/article/new-research-discovery-could-unlock-the-potential-development-of-an-alzheimer-s-treatment/|title=New Research Discovery - Alzheimer\u2019s and Toxicity Pathways|website=BioSpace|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fightaging.org/archives/2019/07/lando-found-to-be-key-to-microglial-clearance-of-amyloid-%ce%b2-and-neuroinflammation/|title=LANDO Found to be Key to Microglial Clearance of Amyloid-\u03b2 and Neuroinflammation|date=2019-07-05|website=Fight Aging!|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stjude.org/media-resources/news-releases/2019-medicine-science-news/lando-pathway-prevents-alzheimers-protein-buildup.html|title=Pathway discovered that prevents buildup of Alzheimer\u2019s protein|website=www.stjude.org|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref><ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":1\" />.  \n\nThe potential for LC3-associated endocytosis to be therapeutic target for the treatment of neurodegenerative diseases including Alzheimer's Disease as well as cancer are of significant promise<ref name=\":1\" />. \n\n== External Links ==\n\n* [https://www.stjude.org/research/departments-divisions/immunology.html St. Jude Children's Research Hospital]\n* [https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Bradlee_Heckmann Research Gate]\n* [https://orcid.org/0000-0002-3271-7183 ORCID]\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox scientist\n| name              = Bradlee L. Heckmann\n| image             = FILE:heckmannA.png\n| nationality       = United States\n| fields            = [[Neuroimmunology]]\n[[Autophagy]]\n[[Alzheimer's Disease]]\n| workplaces        = [[St. Jude Children's Research Hospital]]\n| alma_mater        = Mayo Clinic Coll. of Medicine\n[[University of Kentucky]]\n| thesis_title      = The function and regulation of the G0/G1 Switch Gene 2\n| thesis_url        = https://search.proquest.com/openview/cfe389ce39ce8418e0f84556975e7eeb/1?pq-origsite=gscholar&cbl=18750&diss=y\n| academic_advisors = [[Douglas R. Green]],\nEdmund B. Rucker, III\n| doctoral_advisor  = Jun Liu\n| website           = {{URL|http://www.stjude.org}}\n| other_names       = Brad Heckmann\n| birth_place       = [[Lexington, KY]]\n}}\n  \nBradlee L. Heckmann is an American biologist and neuroimmunologist who currently holds the John H. Sununu Endowed Fellowship<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://orcid.org/0000-0002-3271-7183|title=Bradlee L. Heckmann (0000-0002-3271-7183)|last=ORCID|website=orcid.org|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> in Immunology at [[St. Jude Children's Research Hospital]]. Dr. Heckmann's research is focused on understanding the regulation of inflammatory processes in the central nervous system, with particular emphasis on neurodegenerative diseases including [[Alzheimer's disease|Alzheimer's Disease]]<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Heckmann|first=Bradlee L.|last2=Tummers|first2=Bart|last3=Green|first3=Douglas R.|date=January 2019|title=Crashing the computer: apoptosis vs. necroptosis in neuroinflammation|url=https://www.nature.com/articles/s41418-018-0195-3|journal=Cell Death & Differentiation|language=en|volume=26|issue=1|pages=41\u201352|doi=10.1038/s41418-018-0195-3|issn=1476-5403}}</ref> and the role of the [[autophagy]] machinery in this setting.  \n\n== Education ==\nDr. Heckmann graduated from [[Lexington Catholic High School]] in [[Lexington, Kentucky|Lexington, KY]] prior to attending the [[University of Kentucky]] where he graduated with a Bachelor of Science in Biology. Dr. Heckmann went on to complete his doctoral training in Biochemistry & Molecular Biology at the [[Mayo Clinic College of Medicine and Science|Mayo Clinic College of Medicine]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://search.proquest.com/openview/cfe389ce39ce8418e0f84556975e7eeb/1?pq-origsite=gscholar&cbl=18750&diss=y|title=The function and regulation of the G0/G1 Switch Gene 2 (G0S2) - ProQuest|website=search.proquest.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>. After completing his formal training he joined the laboratory of [[Douglas R. Green|Dr. Douglas R. Green]] at St. Jude as a postdoctoral fellow<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stjude.org/education-training/advanced-training/postdoctoral-fellows.html|title=Postdoctoral Fellows|website=www.stjude.org|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>.\n\n== Research ==\nAfter studying lipid metabolism and components that regulate lipid turnover while at [[Mayo Clinic]], Dr. Heckmann switched his research focus to evaluating the role and regulation of non-canonical [[autophagy]] in the brain<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Heckmann|first=Bradlee L.|last2=Green|first2=Douglas R.|date=2019-03-01|title=LC3-associated phagocytosis at a glance|url=https://jcs.biologists.org/content/132/5/jcs222984|journal=Journal of Cell Science|language=en|volume=132|issue=5|doi=10.1242/jcs.222984|issn=0021-9533|pmid=30787029}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Heckmann|first=Bradlee L.|last2=Boada-Romero|first2=Emilio|last3=Cunha|first3=Larissa D.|last4=Magne|first4=Joelle|last5=Green|first5=Douglas R.|date=2017-11-24|title=LC3-Associated Phagocytosis and Inflammation|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0022283617304187|journal=Journal of Molecular Biology|language=en|volume=429|issue=23|pages=3561\u20133576|doi=10.1016/j.jmb.2017.08.012|issn=0022-2836}}</ref>. These studies ultimately led to Heckmann & [[Douglas R. Green|Green]]'s discovery of a novel form of the [[Endocytosis|endocytic]] trafficking pathway.<ref name=\":0\" /> Heckmann and Green showed that a protein known as [[MAP1LC3B|LC3]] which helps facilitate vesicle trafficking and fusion, most well-known for its role in [[autophagy]], was attached to endosomes that contained [[Amyloid beta|\u03b2-amyloid]]<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Heckmann|first=Bradlee L.|last2=Teubner|first2=Brett J. W.|last3=Tummers|first3=Bart|last4=Boada-Romero|first4=Emilio|last5=Harris|first5=Lacie|last6=Yang|first6=Mao|last7=Guy|first7=Clifford S.|last8=Zakharenko|first8=Stanislav S.|last9=Green|first9=Douglas R.|date=2019-07-25|title=LC3-Associated Endocytosis Facilitates \u03b2-Amyloid Clearance and Mitigates Neurodegeneration in Murine Alzheimer\u2019s Disease|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0092867419306270|journal=Cell|language=en|volume=178|issue=3|pages=536\u2013551.e14|doi=10.1016/j.cell.2019.05.056|issn=0092-8674}}</ref>, a known contributor to Alzheimer's Disease in humans. As such they named the discovery LC3-associated endocytosis (LANDO)<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/robinseatonjefferson/2019/07/22/newly-discovered-cellular-pathway-may-mean-new-approach-for-how-we-treat-alzheimers-and-cancer/|title=Newly Discovered Cellular Pathway May Mean New Approach For How We Treat Alzheimer's And Cancer|last=Jefferson|first=Robin Seaton|website=Forbes|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{